Etymology_raw: Cognate with Abaza адгьы́л (ādg̍ə́l); compare Georgian ადგილი (adgili).
Compare Old Armenian պինչ (pinčʿ).
Cognate with Adyghe лъэ (łă).
From Proto-Circassian *gʷǝ (“heart”).
From Proto-Circassian *ʐə.
From Proto-Circassian zə.
From Proto-Circassian *kʲʼa.
тхьамыкӏ (tḥāməč̣̍) +‎ -гъу (-ġ°)
From Proto-Circassian *ɕʷa
From Proto-Circassian *t͡ʂʰə (“horse”).
(This etymology is missing or incomplete. Please add to it, or discuss it at the Etymology scriptorium.)
From the root ء ث ر‎ (ʾ-ṯ-r).
From the root ح ب ب‎ (ḥ-b-b).
From the root د و ر‎ (d-w-r).
From Proto-Semitic *ʾakal- (root ء ك ل‎ (ʾ-k-l)).
From the root و ق د‎ (w-q-d).
From root ن ظ ر‎ (n-ẓ-r)
From the root ق ط ع‎ (q-ṭ-ʿ).
From Proto-Semitic *bint-. Has the Semitic feminine suffix *-at added to the root *bin- of اِبْن‎ (ibn, “son”).
From root ب ي ت‎ (b-y-t). From Proto-Semitic *bayt-.
Originally a case form of a defective noun تَحْت‎ (taḥt, “location that is below”); see the usage note. From the root ت ح ت‎ (t-ḥ-t).
From the root ت ر ك‎ (t-r-k).
From the root ك ل م‎ (k-l-m)
Synchronically from the root ت ل ل‎ (t-l-l). Ultimately from Proto-Semitic *tall- (“hill”).
Mediopassive of وَقَّفَ‎ (waqqafa, “to stop (transitive), to bring to a stop”), from the root و ق ف‎ (w-q-f); compare وَقَفَ‎ (waqafa, “to stop (intransitive)”).
From the root ج ل س‎ (j-l-s)
From the root ج م ل‎ (j-m-l).
From the root ح و ف‎ (ḥ-w-f).
From the root ح ب ب‎ (ḥ-b-b).
From the root ح ض ر‎ (ḥ-ḍ-r).
From the root ح م ل‎ (ḥ-m-l).
From the root ح م ي‎ (ḥ-m-y).
From the root خ ب ز‎ (ḵ-b-z).
Derived from the active participle of the verb دَرَّ‎ (darra, “to flow copiously”), from the root د ر ر‎ (d-r-r).
From the root د ب ب‎ (d-b-b).
From the root د خ ل‎ (d-ḵ-l).
From the root د ف ع‎ (d-f-ʿ).
From the root د ل ل‎ (d-l-l).
From the root ذ و ب‎ (ḏ-w-b)
From the root ذ ه ب‎ (ḏ-h-b).
From the root ر ب ط‎ (r-b-ṭ).
From the root ر ع د‎ (r-ʿ-d).
From the root ر ف ع‎ (r-f-ʿ).
From the root س و ق‎ (s-w-q).
From the root س ح ب‎ (s-ḥ-b).
From the root س م ع‎ (s-m-ʿ), from Proto-Semitic *šamaʿ-.
From the root س ن ن‎ (s-n-n).
From the root ش ر ق‎ (š-r-q).
From the root ش ع ر‎ (š-ʿ-r).
From the root ص خ ب‎ (ṣ-ḵ-b).

From the root ص غ ر‎ (ṣ-ḡ-r), from Proto-Semitic *ṣ-ɣ-r (“to be small, young”). Cognate with Akkadian 𒌉 (TUR, ṣehru), 𒌉𒁕 (BÀN.DA, ṣehru, “small, young”), Aramaic ܙܥܘܪܐ‎ (zʿūrā, “small”), Ugaritic 𐎕𐎙𐎗 (ṣġr), Hebrew צָעִיר‎ (tsa'ír).
From the root ص ق ع‎ (ṣ-q-ʿ).

From the root ص و ت‎ (ṣ-w-t). The sense “vote” is probably a loan translation from a European language, most likely French voix, but compare also German Stimme and stimmen, Russian голос (golos) and голосовать (golosovatʹ), etc.
From the root ض ر ب‎ (ḍ-r-b).
From the root ظ ف ر‎ (ẓ-f-r), inherited from Proto-Semitic *θ̣upr-, *θ̣ipr-.
From the root ظ ه ر‎ (ẓ-h-r).
From the root ع ل م‎ (ʿ-l-m).
From the root ع م ل‎ (ʿ-m-l). The grammatical “government” meaning is a semantic loan from  Medieval Latin vīs. Compare Hebrew עָמָל‎ (`Amal, “work, deed”)
From the root غ ر ب‎ (ḡ-r-b).
From the roots غ ط ي‎ (ḡ-ṭ-y) and غ ط و‎ (ḡ-ṭ-w). Cognate with Hebrew עָטָה‎ (ʿatá).
From the root غ ن ي‎ (ḡ-n-y), to be free from want, to be rich, to be full; to be full of sound, resonating.
From the root ف ع ل‎ (f-ʿ-l); cognate with Hebrew פָּעַל‎ (pa'ál, “to do”).
From the root ف ه م‎ (f-h-m).
From the root ق و م‎ (q-w-m). Compare Hebrew קָם‎ (kam), Ge'ez ቆመ (ḳomä).
From the root ق د ر‎ (q-d-r).
From the root ق ذ ر‎ (q-ḏ-r).
From the root ق س م‎ (q-s-m).
From the root ق ط ع‎ (q-ṭ-ʿ).
From the root ق ل ب‎ (q-l-b).
From the root ق و و‎ (q-w-w).
From the root ك ث ر‎ (k-ṯ-r). Adverbial accusative of كَثِير‎ (kaṯīr, “many”).
From the root ك س ر‎ (k-s-r), related to breaking.

From the root ك ن س‎ (k-n-s). In Fraenkel’s and Nöldeke’s view the meaning “to sweep” is from  Aramaic כְּנַשׁ‎ / ܟܢܝ‎ (knaš, “to gather; to sweep”), denominal via مِكْنَسَة‎ (miknasa, “broom”). Note Mehri kənūs (“to sweep”).
From the root ل ع ب‎ (l-ʿ-b).
From the root ل و ح‎ (l-w-ḥ). Cognate with Hebrew לוּחַ‎ (lúakh).
From the root خ ل ب‎ (ḵ-l-b).
From the root م ر ض‎ (m-r-ḍ).
Derived from the passive participle of اِسْتَنْقَعَ‎ (istanqaʿa, “to be or become stagnant”), from the root ن ق ع‎ (n-q-ʿ).
From the root م س ك‎ (m-s-k).
From the root م ش ط‎ (m-š-ṭ). Compare Akkadian 𒄑𒂵𒍮 (/mušṭu/, “comb”).
From Proto-Semitic *malk-. Cognate to Hebrew מֶלֶךְ‎ (mélekh, “king”) and מָלַךְ‎ (malákh, “to rule”), and Aramaic מַלְכָּא‎ (malkā, “king”) and מְלַךְ‎ (m'laḵ, “to rule”).
From the root ن و م‎ (n-w-m).
From the root ن ظ ر‎ (n-ẓ-r).
From the root و ص ل‎ (w-ṣ-l).
From the root و ض ع‎ (w-ḍ-ʿ)
From the root و ل د‎ (w-l-d), from Proto-Semitic *walad-. Cognate with Akkadian 𒅇𒌅 (walādum), Aramaic יְלַד‎ (yəlaḏ), Classical Syriac ܝܠܕ‎ (ilaḏ), Hebrew יָלַד‎ (yālaḏ) and Ugaritic 𐎊𐎍𐎄 (yld).
From Arabic كَرَّة‎ (karra).
Compare Old Armenian մագիլ (magil).
From Proto-Avaro-Andian *c̣aʔi, from Proto-North Caucasian *c̣ăjɨ̆.
From Proto-Turkic *ïgač.
From Common Turkic *ālda (“to deceive, fool”), a derivation from Common Turkic *āl (“craftiness; lie; strategy; way of doing”) , whence also dialectal Azerbaijani al (“lie, untruth”).
From Proto-Turkic *ạl- (“to take”). Cognate with Old Turkic 𐰞‎ (al-) Turkish almak, Chuvash ил (il), etc.
From Proto-Turkic *ạt- (“to throw, shoot”). Cognate with Turkish atmak.
From Proto-Turkic *iak- (“to flow”). Cognate with Old Turkic [script needed] (ak-), Turkish akmak, Chuvash юх (juh).
From Proto-Turkic *āń(k). Cognate with Chuvash уйӑх (ujăh) See Turkish ay for more cognates.
From bağ +‎ -la. Cognate with Turkish bağlamak.
Equivalent to baş (“head”) +‎ -la. Cognate with Turkish başlamak. Probably from Proto-Turkic, compare Chuvash пуҫла (puśla, “to start”, transitive).
From bataq +‎ -lıq.
From Proto-Turkic *bat- (“to sink; to fit into, get into”). Cognate with Kazakh бату (batw).
From Proto-Turkic *bạk- (“to look, watch”). Cognate with Turkish bakmak, Crimean Tatar baqmaq, Turkmen bakmak.

From Proto-Turkic *bil- (“to know”)
Cognate with
Old Turkic 𐰋𐰃𐰠‎ (bil-, “to know”),
Turkish bilmek,
Crimean Tatar bilmek,
Uzbek bilmoq (“to know”).
Crimean Tatar bilmek,
Kazakh білу (bilw, “to know”),
Tatar белү (belü)

Morphologically bişmək (“become cooked”) +‎ -ir (“causative suffix”). Cognate with Turkish pişirmek (“to cook”), Kazakh пісіру (pisirw, “to cook”), Tatar пешерү (peşerü, “to cook, to boil”), Uyghur پىشىرماق‎ (pishirmaq, “to cook”).
From Proto-Turkic *büt-, whence also bütün (“all, whole”). Cognate with Turkish bitmek, Chuvash пӗт (pĕt) etc.
Ultimately from Sinitic 茶.
From Proto-Turkic *čebir-. Cognate with Chuvash ҫаврӑн (śavrăn).
From Common Turkic *čeŋe. Cognate with Turkish çene, see there for more.
Borrowed from Persian چنگال‎ (čangâl).
From Proto-Turkic *čẹr (“rotten, foul; to rot; illness; dirt; to be sick, ill; rot; glue; anguish, sorrow”), whence possibly also Azerbaijani çirk (“dirt”). Cognate with Turkish çürümek.

From Old Anatolian Turkish [script needed] (danışmaq), ultimately a derivation of Proto-Turkic *tạnu- (“to know, get to know”) , whence also Azerbaijani tanımaq. Cognate with Karakhanid تَنُشْماقْ‎ (tanušmāq, “to talk to each other”), Ottoman Turkish طانشمق‎ (danışmak, “to advice, counsel”).

From Proto-Turkic *dẹri (“skin”). Cognate with Turkmen deri, Turkish deri,
Kazakh терi (teri),
Karachay-Balkar тери (teri), Kumyk тери (teri), Kyrgyz тери (teri),
Uzbek teri,
Uyghur تېرە‎ (tëre),
Yakut тирии (tirii), Dolgan тирии, Tatar тире (tire) and
Bashkir тире (tire).
From Proto-Turkic *dil, *dɨl (“tongue; language”). Cognate with Turkish dil.
From Proto-Turkic *tog-. Cognate with Old Turkic [script needed] (tugur-, “to give birth to”), Uzbek tugʻmoq (“to give birth to”), Chuvash ту (tu).
From Proto-Turkic *duj- (“to perceive (by ears or nose), notice”). Cognate with Turkish duymak.
From Proto-Turkic *tüŕ (“even, level”).
From Proto-Turkic *ẹĺit-. Cognate with Turkish işitmek, Kazakh есту (estw), Uzbek eshitmoq.
From Proto-Turkic *ēt-. Cognate with Old Turkic 𐰃𐱅‎ (et-, “to make”), Turkish etmek.
From Proto-Turkic *eb (“dwelling place, house”). Cognate with Old Turkic 𐰋‎ (eb), Turkish ev.
From  Proto-Turkic *ẹri-. Cognate with Turkish erimek.
Ultimately from Proto-Turkic *kē(y)t- (“to go (away), to get away”).
From Proto-Turkic *kīr- (“to enter”). Cognate with Old Turkic 𐰚𐰃𐰼‎ (kir- /kir²/), Turkish girmek, Chuvash кӗр (kĕr) etc.
From gizləmək +‎ -t.
From gör (“to see”) +‎ -ün (“[passive suffix]”). Compare Turkish görünmek.
From Proto-Turkic *kȫk (“blue, green”).
From Arabic هَوَاء‎ (hawāʾ).
From Proto-Turkic *īĺč (“work, deed”).
From Persian کنار‎ (kenâr).
From Arabic مَسَافَة‎ (masāfa).
Cognate with Turkish ödemek, etc.
From Proto-Turkic *bōl- (“to become”). See there for cognates.

From Proto-Turkic *ört- (“to cover”), whence also Azerbaijani örpək (“headscarf”).
Cognate with Turkish örtmek (“to cover, shut”), Chuvash витме (vitme, “to cover, protect, close”), etc.
From Proto-Turkic *ol-tur- (“to sit”), causative of *ol-.
From Proto-Turkic *okï-.

Ultimately from Proto-Turkic *oj- (“to play, to jump”), whence also the derivation oyun (“play, game”). Cognate with
Turkish oynamak,
Turkmen oýnamak,
Crimean Tatar oynamaq,
etc.

Ultimately from Proto-Turkic *ȫ- (“to think of, understand, realize”), and its derivations, such as Proto-Turkic *ȫg (“mind, thought, intelligence”), and Proto-Turkic *ȫgre-, its reflexive form. Cognate with Turkish öğretmek (“to teach”) and Turkish öğrenmek (“to learn”). See there for more.

From Proto-Turkic *buŕ-, *boŕ- (“to damage, destroy”).
Cognate with Turkish bozmak, Chuvash пӑс (păs, “break, destroy”), etc.
From Proto-Turkic *kāpuk (“bark; skin; shell”).
From Common Turkic *kač- (“to run away, flee”). Cognate with Turkish kaçmak etc.
Morphologically from qalxmaq (“to rise”) +‎ -dır, with /x/ in qalxmaq being lost via syncope. Cognate with Turkish kaldırmak.
From Proto-Turkic *kaŕgan, compare Chuvash хуран (huran).
From Proto-Turkic *kïr- (“to break, demolish; small; to scrape, shave”). Compare Azerbaijani qırxmaq (“to shave”) which is probably a derivation from the same root. Cognate with Turkish kırmak etc.

From Proto-Turkic *kï̄ŕ (“girl, woman”). Cognate with Bashkir ҡыҙ (qïð), Crimean Tatar qız, Karakalpak qız, Kazakh қыз (qız), Kyrgyz кыз (kız), Old Turkic [script needed] (kïz), Ottoman Turkish قیز‎, Tatar кыз (qız), Turkish kız, Turkmen gyz, Tuvan кыс (kıs), Uyghur قىز‎ (qiz), Uzbek qiz.
From Proto-Turkic *kol (“upper arm”). Cognate with Turkish kol, Crimean Tatar qol etc.
From qop- (“to break off”) +‎ -ar
Form Common Turkic *kōrï-. Cognate with Old Turkic [script needed] (korï-, “to protect”), Uzbek qoʻrimoq (“to protect”).
Likely from Proto-Turkic. Cognates include Turkish korkmak, Kazakh қорқу (qorqw), Uzbek qoʻrqmoq, Chuvash хӑра (hăra).
From Proto-Turkic *ko-. Cognate with Old Turkic [script needed] (kōd-), [script needed] (kōt-, “to put, to set down, to lay, to place”), Turkish koymak, etc.
From Proto-Turkic *kūrt.
From Arabic صَبَاح‎ (ṣabāḥ).
From Old Anatolian Turkish [script needed] (sakla-, “to guard, protect”), ultimately from Proto-Turkic *sạk (“aware, alert”). Cognate with Turkish saklamak.
Ultimately from Arabic شَيْء‎ (šayʾ).
From Proto-Turkic *ses. Cognate with Turkish, Crimean Tatar, Gagauz, Turkish ses, Kazakh сес (ses), Chuvash сасӑ (sasă).
From sın- (“to break”) +‎ -dır (“causative”).
From Proto-Turkic *soŋ (“back, end”). Compare Turkish son below.
A derivation of Proto-Turkic *soŋ (“end”), whence also son. Cognate with Turkish sonra etc.

From Proto-Turkic *sok- (“to pierce, stick into”), which was homonyms to and possibly cognate with Proto-Turkic *sok- (“to hit, beat, crush”). Compare Karakhanid سُقْماق‎ (suqmāq), Turkish sokmak (“to insert”), etc.
From Proto-Turkic *sogï-k. Cognate with Turkish soğuk, Uzbek sovuq, Bashkir һыуыҡ (hïwïq), Chuvash сивӗ (sivĕ) etc.
From Proto-Turkic. Cognate with Turkish süpürmek, Chuvash шӑпӑр (šăpăr, “broom”).
Ultimately from Proto-Turkic *sǖr-, cognate with Turkish sürmek.
Cognate with Old Turkic [script needed] (sürüg).
From Proto-Turkic *tepö.

From Proto-Turkic *dik- (“vertical; to to plant vertically”).
Compare Turkish dikmek (“to sew”), Kumyk тикмек (tikmek, “to sew; to build”) Kazakh тігу (tigw).

From Proto-Turkic *tut- (“to grasp”).
Cognate with Old Turkic 𐱃𐰆𐱃‎ (tut-, “to keep, catch, own”), Turkish tutmak (“to catch, keep”), Bashkir тотоу (totou, “to keep, hold”), Chuvash тытма (tytma, “to keep, hold”), Khakas & Shor тударға (tudarğa, “to keep, hold, catch, seize, rule, hold back”), Kyrgyz тутуу (tutuu, “to catch”), Turkmen tutmak (“to hold, keep, catch, hire, fill”), Tuvan тудар (tudar, “to hold, catch, grab”), Uzbek tutmoq (“to take, hold, catch”), Yakut тут (tut, “to hold, seize, grab, catch”).
From Proto-Turkic *uŕɨ-n, *uŕa-k (“long, far, late”), whence also uzaq (“far, distant”).
Ultimately from Proto-Turkic *bēr- (“to give”). Cognate with Old Turkic [script needed] (ber-, “to give”), Turkish vermek, etc.
Ultimately from Arabic خَبَر‎ (ḵabar).
From Proto-Turkic *yāg.
Morphologically from yanmaq (“to burn”) +‎ -dır
Ultimately from Proto-Turkic *yāĺ (“young, fresh”).
From Common Turkic *yāša-, a derivation from Proto-Turkic *yāĺ.
From Proto-Turkic *yāy (“summer”).
From yellə- +‎ -n.
From Proto-Turkic *yē-. Cognate with Old Turkic [script needed] (ye-, “to eat”), Turkish yemek, etc.
Ultimately from Proto-Turkic *yẹr. Cognate with Old Turkic 𐰘𐰼‎ (yer), 𐰘𐰃𐰼‎ (yir).
From Proto-Turkic *uya. Cognate with Chuvash йӑва (jăva).
From Proto-Turkic *adak (“leg”); however, not a regular Kypchak development thereof (which is аяҡ (ayaq)), but apparently a (now extinct) collateral branch with a peculiar semantic shift.

From Proto-Turkic *āń(k) (“moon, month”).
Cognate with Azerbaijani ay, Turkish, Crimean Tatar ay, Tatar, Kazakh, Kyrgyzай (ay), Southern Altai ай (ay), Uzbek oy, etc.

From Proto-Turkic *ạl- (“to take”).
Cognate with Old Turkic [script needed] (al-, “to take”); Turkish almak, Yakut ыл (ıl, “to take”), Chuvash ил (il, “to take”), etc.

From Proto-Turkic *āŋla- (“to understand”), from Proto-Turkic *āŋ (“intelligence, mind”).
Cognate with Old Uyghur [script needed] (aŋla-, “to understand”); Kyrgyz аңдоо (añdoo, “to understand”), Karachay-Balkar ангыларгъа (añılarğa, “to understand”), Uzbek anglamoq (“to understand”), Uyghur ئاڭلىماق‎ (anglimaq, “to listen; to understand”), Turkish anlamak (“to understand”), Azerbaijani anlamaq (“to understand”).

From Proto-Turkic *agrɨ-g (“pain, illness”), an action noun of *agrɨ- (“to ache; be ill”).
Cognate with
Karakhanid اَغْرِغْ‎ (aɣrïɣ, “pain”),
Old Uyghur ՚՚q̈ryq (aɣrïɣ, “pain, illness”),
Kazakh ауру (awrw, “illness; ill; to be ill”), Kyrgyz оору (ooru), Southern Altai оору (ooru),
Uzbek ogʻriq (“pain, ilness”),
Uyghur ئاغرىق‎ (aghriq, “illness”),
Khakas ағырығ (ağırığ, “illness; ill”),
Tuvan аарыг (aarıg, “illness, pain”),
Yakut ыарыы (ıarıı, “pain, disease”),
Turkish ağrı (“pain, ache”).

From Common Kypchak *ayaq, from Proto-Turkic *adak (“foot, leg”).
Compare Old Turkic 𐰑𐰴‎ (adaq, “leg, foot”).
See also аҙаҡ (aðaq).

From *ayt- (“to say, utter”), from Proto-Turkic *ayɨt- (“to say; ask”), which (as seen in Old Uyghur, Yakut, Chuvash cognates) was originally a causative form of an earlier *ay- (“to say”).
Compare to
Tatar әйтү (äytü, “to say”),
Kazakh айту (aytw, “to say”),
Kyrgyz айтуу (aytuu, “to say”),
Crimean Tatar aytmaq (“to say”),
Uzbek aytmoq (“to say”),
Uyghur ئېيتماق‎ (ëytmaq, “to say”),
Kumyk айтмакъ (aytmaq, “to say”),
dialectal Khakas айт- (ayt-, “to say”), айыт- (ayıt-, “to sing”),
Turkish ayıtmak (“to say”);
Old Uyghur [script needed] (ajït-, “to have/make/let sb. say”),
Yakut ыйыт- (ıyıt-, “to ask”),
Chuvash ыйт (yjt, “to ask”).

From Proto-Turkic *iāčɨg (“bitter, acid”).
A palatal parallel development, compare Bashkir асы (asï, “bitter, sour”) from the same archetype.

From Proto-Turkic *bat-gak (“sticky mud, bog”), from *bat- (“to sink, get bogged/stuck in mud”).
Cognate with
Kazakh батпақ (batpaq),
Kyrgyz баткак (batkak),
Shor патқақ (patqaq),
Karachay-Balkar батхакъ (batxaq, “clay, mud”),
Uzbek botqoq,
Uyghur پاتقاق‎ (patqaq, “sticky mud, bog”),
Turkmen batga (“swamp, bog”),
Turkish batak (“swamp, bog”).

From Common Kypchak *baw, from Common Turkic *bāğ (“rope, binder”), from Proto-Turkic *b(i)ā- (“to bind, fasten”).
Cognate with
Old Uyghur [script needed] (bağ, “band, binder; bond”);
Kazakh бау (baw, “cord, binder”),
Kyrgyz боо (boo, “cord, binder”),
Southern Altai буу (buu, “cord”),
Crimean Tatar bav (“knot”),
Uzbek bogʻ (“cord; bundle”),
Turkish bağ (“connection”),
Yakut быа (bıa, “cord, lace”), etc.

From Proto-Turkic *bīr (“one”).
Cognate with
Old Turkic 𐰋𐰃𐰼‎ (bir, “one”), Turkish bir (“one, once”).

From Proto-Turkic *bēr- (“to give”).
Cognate with Old Turkic -𐰋𐰃𐰼 (bér-, “to give”);  Turkish vermek, Yakut биэр (bier), Chuvash пар (par, “to give”), etc.

Cognate with
Karakhanid [script needed] (butaq, “branch, twig”);
Kazakh бұтақ (butaq),
Kyrgyz бутак (butak),
Southern Altai будак (budak, “branch, twig”),
Uzbek butoq (“branch, twig”), etc.
From Proto-Turkic *bōl- (“to become”).
From Persian درست‎ (dorost, “correct”).

From *yebiĺ(č) (“wet”), from Proto-Turkic *yebi- (“to soak, become wet”).
Cognate with Tatar юеш (yuyeş, “wet”), Karaim йувюш / йӱвӱш / йӱвӱс / йивис (“wet”).

From Common Kypchak *egin "grain crop", from *ekin "cultivated land; crops grown on such land"; from  Proto-Turkic *ek- (“to sow”).
Cognate with
Old Uyghur [script needed] (ekin, “arable land, tilled land”);
Kazakh егін (egin, “grain crops”),
Kyrgyz эгин (egin, “grain crops”),
Uzbek ekin (“farm crop”),
Uyghur ئېكىن‎ (ëkin, “arable land; farm crop”),
Turkish ekin (“farm crop”).

The only reliable cognate is Kazakh ену (enw, “to enter, go in”). Thus, this is a very peculiar regional feature shared by only these two languages.
Generally thought to derive from Proto-Turkic *ēn- (“to go down”),.
However, no adequate explanation has been presented as to how this peculiar semantic transformation ("go down" > "enter") could have taken place, and why only in these two languages but not elsewhere.

Probably of Iranian origin (compare Persian خوب‎ (“good”)), formally from Proto-Slavic *xubъ + -ав (-av). Cognate with Macedonian убав (ubav).
From Proto-Slavic *čьrta.
From Proto-Slavic *ǫgъlъ, from Proto-Indo-European *h₂engulos (“joint?”), from *h₂eng- (“corner”).
Uncertain. Possibly of pre-Roman origin, or of Gothic origin. Compare Spanish amagar (“to threaten”) and  Portuguese esmagar.
Borrowed from French attraper.
From Old Occitan, from Medieval Latin, Late Latin bursa, from Ancient Greek βύρσα (búrsa). Doublet of borsa.
From camí +‎ -ar.
From Latin corrigia, attested from 1271.
Possibly from Latin de ex pressum, or more likely from Old Catalan despuix, despuis, depuis (itself from Latin de post) + aprés.
From Old Occitan [Term?] (compare Occitan ensenhar), from Vulgar Latin insignāre, present active infinitive of insignō (compare French enseigner, Spanish enseñar), from Latin signō.
From Old Occitan, from Medieval Latin friscus, frescus, of Germanic origin, from Proto-Germanic *friskaz. More at English fresh.
From Italian pantano, attested from the 14th century.
From Old Occitan [Term?], from Vulgar Latin *passāre, from Latin passum, supine of pando (“I stretch, I spread out”). Compare Occitan passar, French passer, Spanish pasar, Italian passare.
From Old Occitan, from Vulgar Latin *pendicāre, from Latin pendēre, present active infinitive of pendeō, from Proto-Italic *pendēō, from Proto-Indo-European *(s)pend- (“to pull; to spin”)
From Old Occitan, from Vulgar Latin *pīccāre, itself a derivative of Latin pīcus or of onomatopoetic origin.

From a variant of Old Occitan [Term?], from Late Latin pausāre, present active infinitive of pausō, influenced in meaning by Latin pōnō. Compare French poser, Occitan pausar, Spanish posar, Portuguese pousar, Italian posare.
Borrowed from Latin praeparāre, present active infinitive of praeparō (“I prepare”).

From Old Occitan, from Latin *podiāre, from Latin podium. Compare Occitan pujar, Aragonese puyar, Portuguese pojar, Italian poggiare; cf. also French appuyer, Spanish apoyar, Italian appoggiare, from a Vulgar Latin *appodiāre.
From sacsar +‎ -ejar.

From Old Occitan (compare Occitan sortir), from Latin sortīrī (“to select”) (present active infinitive of sortior), probably influenced by surrectus (through a Vulgar Latin form *surctus and its derivatives, possibly through a verb *surrectīre, surctīre; cf. also Old Catalan surt, surta).
From Old Occitan, from Late Latin taleare or taliāre, present active infinitive of taliō, from Latin talea.

From Medieval Latin, from Vulgar Latin *tirō, tirāre, from Proto-Germanic *teraną (“to tear, tear away, rip or snatch off, pull violently, tug”) (through Gothic *𐍄𐌹𐍂𐌰𐌽 (*tiran)), from Proto-Indo-European *der- (“to tear, tear apart”). Alternatively Late Latin *martyrāre, possibly with influence from Latin trahō. Compare French tirer, Italian tirare.
From Old Occitan, from Vulgar Latin *ungla, syncopated form of Latin ungula, from unguis, ultimately from Proto-Indo-European *h₃negʰ-.
From Old Czech chot, from Proto-Slavic *chotь. Related to chtít.

From Proto-Nakh *butt.
From Proto-Nakh *dāli.
From Proto-Nakh *kōḳ.
From Proto-Nakh *qēra.
From Proto-Nakh *lātte.
From Proto-Nakh *moṭṭ.

From Proto-Nakh *pχā. Cognate with Ingush пхьан (pḥan, “hornbeam”). Associated with several weapon names, because they were made of hornbeam: Chechen пха (pχa, “arrow”), пха, пхьа (pχa, pḥa, “shield”), пхердукъ (pχerduq̇, “spear”).
From сан (san, “my, mine”); related to сирла (sirla, “light, bright, clear”) and серло (serlo, “light, brightness, illumination”).
Cognate with Ingush ха (χa). Related to Georgian ხანი (xani). This etymology is incomplete. You can help Wiktionary by elaborating on the origins of this term.
From Proto-Nakh *xi.
From Proto-Nakh *cħa.
From Proto-Nakh *c̣e (“name”).
From Proto-Nakh *jobq̇.
Borrowed from Russian обед (obed).
Related to Tatar апа (apa), from Old Turkic apa.
Compare Tatar ут (ut).
From Proto-Turkic *kȫk.
From Proto-Turkic *gīr- (“to enter”). Cognate with Old Turkic 𐰚𐰃𐰼‎ (kir- /kir²/), Turkish girmek, Azerbaijani girmək etc.
From Proto-Turkic *gül. Cognate with Turkish and Azerbaijani -gil (“someone's home or family”), Yakut күүлэ (küüle, “entrance hall”).
From Proto-Turkic *buŕ- / *boŕ- (“to damage, destroy”). Cognate with Azerbaijani pozmaq, Bashkir боҙоу (boðou).
Related to Turkish bulut and Yakut пылыт (pılıt), from Proto-Turkic *bulït, .
From Proto-Turkic *biarŋak.
From Proto-Turkic *yāŕ. Cognate with Turkish yaz (“summer”).
Historically from тăв (tăv) (< тав (taw) < тау (tau)), from Proto-Turkic *tāg.
From Proto-Turkic *kāŕ, compare Turkish kaz.
From Proto-Turkic *dɨl.

From Proto-Turkic *dik- (“vertical; to to plant vertically”).
Compare Azerbaijani dikmək (“to bury”) dik (“upright, vertical”), tikmək (“to sew”); Turkish dikmek (“to sew”), Kumyk тикмек (tikmek, “to sew; to build”) Kazakh тігу (tigw).
Related to Turkish diş.
From Proto-Chukotko-Kamchatkan *ðəlɣə (“finger”). Compare also Koryak йәлгәлӈән, Alutor тылгылӈын and Itelmen луфԓич.
Cognate with Japhug amdzɯ (Zhang, Jacques, and Lai, 2019).

Simplified from 點 (黑 → 灬). Note that 黑 changed from being on the left to being 灬, underneath. Compare 黙 (from 默), which retains the 里, and 黒, which is the simplification in isolation.
Current form is graphically 占 + 灬.
From Proto-Sino-Tibetan *m-kul (“twenty; all”); cognate with 昆 (OC *kuːn, “swarming”), Tibetan ཀུན (kun, “all”), Burmese အကုန် (a.kun, “all”) (Benedict, 1972; STEDT).

From Proto-Sino-Tibetan *m/g-(r)wa-ŋ/k/t (“horn; angle; corner”) (STEDT). Cognate with Tibetan རྭ (rwa, “horn”), Garo grong (“horn”), Jingpho nrung (n̩³¹ ʒuŋ³³, “horn”), Chepang रोङः (roŋʔ, “horn”), 觡 (OC *kraːɡ, “antler”). The Tibeto-Burman *-ŋ final variant is reflected in 觥 (OC *kʷraːŋ, “drinking vessel made from animal horn”) (Schuessler, 2007). Possibly also related to 鹿 (OC *b·roːɡ, “deer”) (Sagart, 1999).
A derivative is 餃 (“stuffed dumpling”), named for its horn-like shape (Norman, 1988).
It is probably unrelated with Proto-Indo-European *ḱr̥h₂nós (“horn”) ( < *ḱerh₂- (“horn”)) and Proto-Semitic *ḳarn- (“horn”) despite the phonological and semantic resemblance between the three.
Proto-Celtic *bawā. Compare French boue (“mud”), from Gaulish *bauā.
From berw (“boiling”) +‎ -i.
From Middle Welsh bwrt, from Old English bord (compare Irish bord); doublet of bord.
From Proto-Brythonic *catarno, from Proto-Celtic *katus (“battle”). See cad.
From cau +‎ -ad.
From cangau, plural of cainc (“branch”) (from Proto-Celtic *kankā),  +‎ -en (singulative suffix).
From casgl (“collection”) +‎ -u.
Cognate with Cornish gwari and Breton c'hoari.
Cognate with Cornish kelmi, Breton koulmañ.
From Proto-Brythonic *klüwid, from Proto-Celtic *klusīti, from Proto-Indo-European *ḱlew-.
Clipping of cyfodi, from cyf- +‎ odi.

From Proto-Celtic *koudeti, from Proto-Indo-European *(s)kewdʰ- (“to cover, wrap, encase”),  +‎ -io (forming verbnouns). Cognate with Cornish cuthe, Breton cuzaff, English hide, Latin custōs, Ancient Greek κεύθω (keúthō, “to conceal”), Sanskrit कुहरम् (kuharam, “cave”).
From cwymp.
From cyf- +‎ rhif.
From Proto-Brythonic *dalg-, from Proto-Indo-European *delgʰ-. Cognate with Latin indulgeo.

Contraction of older deau (“right; south”), from Proto-Celtic *dexsos (“right”). Cognate with Cornish dyhow, Breton dehou, Irish deas, Scottish Gaelic deas, Manx jiass.
The sense "south" comes from the fact that the south is on the right-hand side of a person facing east.
Borrowed from Latin discō (“I learn”). Cognate to Breton deskiñ and Cornish dyski, from the same origin.
Borrowed from Old English ford
Ultimately from Proto-Indo-European *ǵʰeh₁- (“to leave behind, abandon”).
From gorchudd +‎ -io.

From Old Welsh guor (“over”) +‎ phenn (“head”) (see penn).
Cognate with Cornish gorfedna, Breton gourfennañ.
From Proto-Celtic *u̯o-stutā (see go-), from Proto-Indo-European *steh₂-.
From Proto-Celtic *grendsmu, from Proto-Indo-European *gʰredʰ-. Cognate with Latin gradus (“step”).

The variant gwddwg is cognate with Old Breton guodoc (Middle Breton gouzouc, Breton gouzoug, goûg), but it is difficult to explain the alternation between -wg, -w, and -f. The oldest form of the word cited in Geiriadur Prifysgol Cymru is the Middle Welsh plural form gedueu (13th century; = modern gyddfau), while the soft mutation forms wðwc, wddf, and wddw are all attested in the 14th century, indicating that the alternation is very old.

Back-formation from gwneuthur, from Middle Welsh gwneuthur, altered from *gwreithur with -n- from gwnïo (“to sew”), from Proto-Celtic *wregeti (compare Cornish gwra (“he does, makes”), Breton gra (“he does, makes”), Old Irish fairged (“they made”)), from Proto-Indo-European *werǵ- (compare English work). Middle Welsh preserved the -r- in the preterite: gwreith (“I did, made”), goruc (“he did, made”).
gwth +‎ -io
From gyr (“drive, thrust; flock, drove”) +‎ -u.
Cognate with Breton moan, Cornish moon.
Ultimately from Proto-Indo-European *med- (“measure; advise”).This etymology is incomplete. You can help Wiktionary by elaborating on the origins of this term.

Suppletive verb; verbal noun from Middle Welsh mynet, from Proto-Brythonic *moned (compare Cornish mones, Breton mont), verbal noun of Proto-Celtic *monītor (compare Middle Irish muinithir (“goes around”)), from Proto-Indo-European *menH- (compare Umbrian menes (“will come”), Lithuanian mìnti (“to trample, scutch”)). Indicative forms from Proto-Celtic *ageti (“to drive”) (compare Old Irish aigid), from Proto-Indo-European *h₂eǵ- (compare Latin agō). The forms in el- are from Proto-Celtic *ɸel- (“to approach, drive”), from Proto-Indo-European *pelh₂- (compare Latin pellō (“strike, drive”), Epic Greek πίλναμαι (pílnamai, “approach”).
From pell (“far (away), distant, remote”) +‎ -ter.
From Latin probō (“to test”).
pwdr +‎ -u. Cognate with Cornish pedri.

From rhuthr (“rush”, noun) +‎ -o, ultimately from Proto-Indo-European *h₃rew- (“to hurry”). Cognate with Middle Irish rúatharaigid (“makes a rush or onset”), from rúathar, rúathur m (“onrush, onset, attack”).
From sain +‎ -io.
sych (“dry”) +‎ -u.
Ultimately from Proto-Indo-European *terh₁- (“to rub, turn; pierce”).
According to Matasovic, from a non-Indo-European language, but Pokorny suggests Proto-Indo-European *terkʷ- (“to twist, spin”).  Cognate with Cornish terri, Breton torriñ.
From tro +‎ -i.
Perhaps ultimately from Proto-Indo-European *ten- (“stretch, extend”).
From ym- +‎ gadael (“leave”)
From ym- +‎ dangos.
See ym-. Cognate with Irish imeall.
From ysgub +‎ -o.

From Old Norse annarr, from Proto-Germanic *anþeraz (“second, other”).
From Old Danish athræ, Old Norse ædr, from Proto-Germanic *ēþrǭ (“vein”). Related to German Ader.
Equivalent to be- +‎ tale (“to speak”), from Middle Low German betalen, compare German bezahlen. A compound with the Germanic verb *talōną (“to tell; to count”).
Borrowed from Middle Low German bliven, from Old Saxon bilīƀan, from Proto-Germanic *bilībaną, cognate with German bleiben (“to remain”). In the sense “to become", it has replaced older vorde.
Derived from the verb.
From Old Danish fange, borrowed from Middle Low German vangen (“to catch”), from vān, from Proto-Germanic *fanganą. Doublet of få (“to get”).

Older Danish farge, from Middle Low German varwe, verwe, from *Old Saxon farwi, *farawi (“colour”), from Proto-Germanic *farwō, from Proto-Indo-European *per-, *perḱ- (“motley, coloured”). Cognate with Old High German farawa (“color”) (German Farbe), Old High German faro (“colored”), Latin pulcher (“beautiful, sheen”), Ancient Greek περκνός (perknós, “multicolored”), Old Irish earc (“spotted”).

From Old Danish feye, borrowed from Middle Low German vegen, from Proto-Germanic *fegōną, cognate with Old High German vegōn, German fegen. Usually associated with Old Norse fága (“to adorn, polish”), Middle Low German vāgen, from Proto-Germanic *fēgōną, but the details are unclear.

From Middle Low German vluchten, compare German flüchten. Derived from the noun Danish flugt, from Middle Low German vlucht, from Proto-Germanic *fluhtiz (“flight”), cognate with English flight and German Flucht.

A merger of two related verbs: 1. Old Norse hengja (“to hang (transitive)”), from Proto-Germanic *hangijaną, cognate with German hängen; and 2. Old Norse hanga (“to hang (intransitive)”), from Proto-Germanic *hanhaną, cognate with English hang and German hangen. In the past tense, Danish still distinguishes transitive hængte from intransitive hang (though they are often mixed up).
Likely related to næppe (“hardly at all”)

From Middle Low German lēren, from Proto-Germanic *laizijaną, cognate with German lehren (“teach”), Dutch leren, and Gothic 𐌻𐌰𐌹𐍃𐌾𐌰𐌽 (laisjan). Late Old Norse læra, Norwegian lære, and Swedish lära are also borrowed form Low German.
From Old Norse regna, from Proto-Germanic *regnōną, cognate with English rain and German regnen. Derived from the noun *regną, cf. Danish regn.
Compare German schlimm.
From stå (“stand”) and op (“up”). Compare opstå.
From Middle Low German stecken, from Old Saxon stekan.
From Old Danish siunkæ, from Old Norse *sinkwa (east) / søkkva (west), from Proto-Germanic *sinkwaną, cognate with Swedish sjunka, English sink, German sinken, Dutch sinken, Gothic 𐍃𐌹𐌲𐌵𐌰𐌽 (sigqan).
From Old Danish wogge, from Old Norse vagga (accusative, dative, genitive vǫggu), cognate with Swedish vagga. Derived form the verb vaga (see the following word).
From Proto-Mongolic *arca, compare East Yugur hrca (“cypress”).
From Proto-Finno-Ugric *käte.
Compound of an- (“on, at”) +‎ zünden (“to ignite, kindle”). Akin to Old English ontendan, Swedish antända, Norwegian antenne.
From a Baltic language. Compare Old Prussian ansis (“hook, latch”) and Latvian osa. Cognate to Finnish ansa and Votic aasa.
From abi +‎ kaasa.
From Proto-Finnic *alla.
From erk (“alert”, noun), see there for further etymology. Compare Finnish herätä.

Related to Finnish enne.
Allegedly coined ex nihilo by Johannes Aavik in the 20th century, but compare Finnish esine.
Cognate to Votic ääli and Livonian ēļ. Possibly a cognate to Finnish ääni, in which case the sound change n -> l would have happened in Estonian, Votic and Livonian.
Possibly from Proto-Germanic *hakkōną. Alternatively of Baltic origin; compare Latvian sākt (“to start”) and Lithuanian šokti.
Onomatopoeic, from heli. Cognate with Finnish helistä, Veps heläitä and Votic elisä.

Possibly from Proto-Finnic *koneh (“magic”) (whence Karelian koneh (“magic”), Finnish kone (“machine, trick”)).

Of Finno-Samic origin. Cognate with Finnish rinta. Alternatively of Germanic origin, from Proto-Norse *strinða-. Compare Old Norse strind (“border, side, land”) and Norwegian strind (“slice, line, row”). This is unlikely due to the difference in meaning.

From Proto-Finnic *se, ultimately from Proto-Uralic *śe. cognate to Finnish se, Votic se, Erzya се (se, “this, that”), Khanty си (si, “that over yonder; now, then”), and Nganasan [script needed] (sete, “he, she”).
Of Finnic origin. Cognate to Finnish sekoittaa and Livonian sie’ggõ.
From üks +‎ -ndama. Compare Finnish yhdentää.
Onomatopoetic. A similar root is seen in Livonian ūška (“worm”). Possibly from Old East Slavic ужь (užĭ).
Derived from valvama (“to guard”), contracted from original *valvatama.
From Ancient Greek ἄκρα (ákra)
Inherited from Ancient Greek ἀπόστασις (apóstasis).
From αρχή (archí, “the beginning”) +‎ -ίζω (-ízo).
From Ancient Greek βαδίζω (badízō).
From Koine Greek βράζω (brázō) from Ancient Greek βράσσω (brássō, “shake violently”).
From Ancient Greek γίγνομαι (gígnomai)
From Ancient Greek γράμμα (grámma). Morphologically γράφω (gráfo) +‎ -μα (-ma, result noun suffix).
From the Ancient Greek γρᾰμμή (grammḗ).
From Byzantine Greek ἐγύρισα (egúrisa), aorist of Byzantine Greek γυρνῶ (gurnô).
The earlier form is δίδω (dído), from Byzantine Greek δίδω (dídō), from Ancient Greek δίδωμι (dídōmi), from Proto-Indo-European *dédeh₃ti, reduplicated present of *deh₃- (“to give”).
Inherited from Ancient Greek δρόμος (drómos).
From Ancient Greek δύναμις (dúnamis).
From Ancient Greek ἐγκαταλείπω. Morphologically, (εν-) εγ- (“in”) +‎ κατα- (“totally”) +‎ λείπω (“leave”).
From Byzantine Greek ἐδῶ (edô), from a metathetic variant of Ancient Greek ὧδε (hôde).
From Ancient Greek ἦχος (êkhos)

From Medieval Byzantine Greek κάθομαι (“I stay, reside”) from Ancient Greek κάθημαι (káthēmai, “to sit, to sit down, to be idle”).
The perfective stem καθισ- as in simple past κάθισα (káthisa), from aorist Ancient Greek ἐκάθισᾰ/κάθισᾰ of verb καθίζω (kathízō).
The second perfective stem κατσ- e.g. έκατσα (ékatsa), from εκάθισα (ekáthisa) (with omission of /i/ & [θs] > [ts]) of verb καθίζω (kathízō).
From Ancient Greek καίω (kaíō) and Mediaeval καίγω (kaígō), from Proto-Hellenic *kayyō. Also see καύση (káfsi, “burning”).
From Ancient Greek κᾰκός (kakós).
From Ancient Greek κάμνω (kámnō), from Proto-Indo-European *kem(H)- (“to be tired”).

Sense pole: from Ancient Greek κοντός (“pole”) (noun).
Sense short: from the Hellenistic Koine Greek κοντός (kontós, “short”) (adjective) from the ancient sense Ancient Greek κοντός (“pole”) which referred to shorter kinds of poles, hence the sense shortness.
From Ancient Greek κόσμος (kósmos).
From Hellenistic Koine Greek κρύβω, from the ancient κρύπτω (“hide”) from the perfective stem κρυψ- in the pattern of -ψ- > -β- as in κλέπτω (klépto), κλεψ- > κλέβω (klévo, “steal”).
See Etymology at λιώνω.
From Ancient Greek λόγος (lógos).
From Medieval Byzantine Greek μαθαίνω from the aorist stem μαθ‑ (ἔμαθον) of ancient Ancient Greek verb μανθάνω (manthánō, “know, understand”) and metaplasm ‑αίνω.
From Byzantine Greek μύτη (mútē), from Ancient Greek μύτις (mútis, “snout”). Displaced earlier Ancient Greek ῥίς (rhís).
From Byzantine Greek νύχιν (núkhin), inherited from Ancient Greek ὀνύχιον (onúkhion), diminutive of ὄνυξ (ónux), ultimately from Proto-Indo-European *h₃negʰ-.
From Ancient Greek ἐξεῦρον (exeûron), aorist of ἐξευρίσκω (exeurískō, “to find out”), from εὑρίσκω (heurískō, “to find”) (whence Modern βρίσκω (vrísko)).
From Ancient Greek ξύλον (xúlon).
From Ancient Greek ὁδηγῶ (hodēgô), contracted form of ὁδηγέω (hodēgéō).
From Mediaeval Byzantine Greek ὄμορφος (ómorphos) < ἔμορφος (émorphos), from the Ancient Greek εὔμορφος (eúmorphos), from εὖ (eû) + μορφή (morphḗ).
From Medieval Byzantine παλιός from Ancient Greek παλαιός (palaiós).
From the Ancient Greek πᾰχῠ́ς (pakhús).
Backformation from Ancient Greek ἀπέθανε (apéthane) the third person singular aorist of ἀποθνῄσκω (apothnḗiskō, “die”).
From Ancient Greek περιμένω (periménō, “-”).

From Ancient Greek ὑπάγω (hupágō, “bring under”) in its Hellenistic sense "go", through its imperfect tense ὑπῆγον (hupêgon) > mediaeval ὑπῆγα (hupêga) which was wrongly analysed as ὑ- + πῆγα (instead of ὑπ- +) and a formation of a new mediaeval present tense + -αίνω (-aínō), πηγαίνω (pēgaínō), in the familiar pattern of aorist - present like ἔμαθα (ἔmatha) - μαθαίνω (mathaíno, “learn”). The form πάω (páo), with silenced [ɣ] for <γ> of mediaeval ὑπάγω.Also see the imperative άμε! (áme!), parallel form of πήγαινε! (pígaine!) and the mediaeval types ὑπαγαίνω (hupagaínō), ἀπηγαίνω (apēgaínō).
From Byzantine Greek [Term?], from an aphetic form of Ancient Greek ὀπίσω (opísō).
From Ancient Greek πληρόω (plēróō, “to complete”). For semantic development, compare Hebrew שילם \ שִׁלֵּם‎ (shilém, “to pay”, literally “to complete”).
From Ancient Greek ποτέ (poté).
From Ancient Greek ποῦ (poû), from Proto-Indo-European *kʷos.
From Byzantine Greek ῥαβδίν (rhabdín), inherited from Ancient Greek ῥαβδίον (rhabdíon), a diminutive of ῥάβδος (rhábdos).
From Ancient Greek ῥέω.
From Ancient Greek σείω.
From Ancient Greek σκέπω (sképō)
From Ancient Greek σπῶ (spô)/σπάω (spáō) + -άζω (-ázo). Also see σπάω (spáo).
From Byzantine Greek ὁσπίτιον (hospítion), from Latin hospitium (“lodgings”). Compare Albanian shtëpi. Displaced earlier Ancient Greek οἶκος (oîkos).
From Medieval Byzantine Greek σπρώχνω (sprṓkhnō), from Ancient Greek προωθῶ (proōthô) / προωθέω (proōthéō, “push forward, propel”) by liaison with pronouns, or from an unattested ancient *εἰσπροωθῶ.
From Ancient Greek στῆθος (stêthos).
Inherited from Ancient Greek σύζυγος (súzugos, “mate, yoked together”), from συ(ν) (su(n), “together”) +‎ ζυγός (zugós, “yoke, pair”), from Proto-Indo-European *yewg- (“to join, tie together”).
Learnedly from Ancient Greek σχίζω (skhízō). See σκίζω (skízo).
From Byzantine Greek τελειώνω (teleiṓnō), from Ancient Greek τελειῶ (teleiô), contracted form of τελειόω (teleióō, “complete, make perfect”) + -ώνω (-óno, suffix for verbs).
Inherited from Ancient Greek τρέχω (trékhō), from Proto-Indo-European *dʰregʰ- (“to run”).

A suppletive verb; Latin vādō (“I go”) supplies the present tense and īre, present active infinitive of the synonymous eō, supplies the future and conditional.
The all- forms derive from Middle French aller, from Old French aler (with subjunctive aill- and other forms with all-), from Vulgar Latin *alō (attested in the 7th century Reichenau Glosses). 
Many explanations have been proposed for the etymology of this all- stem but none has met with a unanimous agreement among philologists. The all- stem has traditionaly been explained as deriving from Latin ambulāre via or together with ambler (compare Old Occitan amblar, Italian ambiare, Romanian umbla), but this explanation is phonologically problematic; ambler is additionally more likely a borrowing from Old Occitan. Several theories have been put forth since the 17th century to explain how ambulare could have become aller.
Since at least the 18th century, some have suggested that aller derives not from Latin but from Celtic, Gaulish *aliu, from Proto-Celtic zero grade *ɸal-. Compare Welsh elwyf (“I may go”), Cornish ellev (“I may go”), from full grade *ɸel- (see mynd for more). This theory is however phonetically problematic.
Another theory was proposed in 1934 by E.F. Parker, suggesting that aller derives from a Late Latin stem *allare which would have been formed out of allatum, past participle of adfero ("to bring"). The idiomatic phrase allatum esse ("to be brought") is recorded in Classical Latin and would have become very common in Northern France with a meaning derivation from being brought to to have been to, in which the past participle *allatus would have been taken as meaning to go and would have then inspired a new infinitive allare (allatus wouldn't have been felt any more as being the same verb as adferre due to particular dissemblance between its stems). This new stem allare would have then been used in suppletion for the Gallo-Roman verb to go as it's infinitive ire had already been forgotten (though it had already formed the future and conditional stem of this verb) and the monosyllabic forms of the present indicative conjugation had already been replaced with those of vadere.
Franco-Provençal allar and Friulan lâ (“to go”) (compare lin (“we go”), lât (“gone”)) are from the same source, whatever it may be.
From Old French bord, from Frankish *bord.

From Middle French brusler “to burn” from Old French brusler, bruller (“to burn”), a conflation of bruir (“to burn”) (from Frankish *brōjan (“to burn, scald”), from Proto-Germanic *brōaną “to scald”, from Proto-Indo-European *bʰerw-, *bʰrew- “to boil, seethe”), and usler (“to scorch”), from Latin ustulāre (“to scorch”). 
Compare also Italian bruciare, from a Vulgar Latin form *brusiō, which is probably related, as well as brustolare. The initial br- has had other origins proposed, such as from a Gaulish source, or from a corruption of a form *combustulāre, from a change of prefix of ambustulāre, influenced by combustus. Akin to German brühen (“to scald”), Dutch broeien (“to heat”). More at broil, brew.

From Old French coper, colper (“to cut off”), probably, derived from cop (“blow”), colp (modern coup), with its meaning coming from the idea of cutting off with a blow. It may correspond to a Vulgar Latin verb *colpāre, syncopated form of *colaphāre, from Latin colaphus (compare Old Spanish golpar, colpar, Old Portuguese golpar, golbar). Alternatively, possibly from Vulgar Latin *cuppāre (“to behead”), from Latin caput (“head”), although this is unlikely.

From Middle French entendre and Old French entendre, from Latin intendere, present active infinitive of intendō (“to turn one's attention, to strain”).

From Middle French, Old French guarder, from Frankish *wardon, from Proto-Germanic *ward-, corresponding to garde +‎ -er. Compare Italian guardare, Spanish guardar, English guard, ward.
From Middle French genner, from Old French gehisner, derivative of gehine (“torture resulting from confession, embarrassment”), of Frankish origin. Synchronically analysable as gêne +‎ -er.

Comparable to Phoenician 𐤀𐤃𐤌‎ (ʾdm, “man, earthling”), Ugaritic 𐎀𐎄𐎎 (ảdm, “man; red earth, red ochre”), Old South Arabian 𐩱𐩵𐩣‎ (“vassals, subjects”), Ge'ez ዶም (dom, “slave”), Akkadian 𒀀𒁕𒄠𒈬 (a-da-am-mu /adamu/, “blood”), Akkadian 𒀀𒁕𒈠𒌈 (a-da-ma-tum /adamātu/, “dark red earth or dye”), Akkadian 𒀀𒁕𒈬 (a-da-mu /adamu/, “a red garment”), Akkadian 𒀀𒁕𒈬 (a-da-mu /adamu/, “an important or noble person”). The meaning range points to these words being extensions from Proto-Semitic *dam- (“blood”), compare the Palestinian Aramaic forms of it אדם‎ / אידם‎ / ܐܕܡ‎ (ʾəḏem, “blood”). The meaning development could be any of
“blood” → “red earth”, “red ochre” → “earthling” or
“blood” → “man”, as blood is a main ingredient of humans or
“blood” → “red earth”, “red ochre” → “the dye to paint idols” → hence “an idol” → “an effigy, a likeness” → “a man” or
“blood” → “blood sacrifice to appease an idol” → hence “an idol” → “an effigy, a likeness” → “a man”,
compare Arabic دُمْيَة‎ (dumya, “statue, idol; effigy, likeness; doll, puppet”), دَمَّ‎ (damma, “to bedaub”).
Compare Ugaritic 𐎀𐎅𐎁 (ảhb).

From earlier बाजना (bājnā), from Sanskrit वाद्यते (vādyate). Compare Nepali बज्नु (bajnu), Gujarati વાગવું (vāgvũ), Marathi वाजणे (vāj̈ṇe), Assamese বজা (boza).
From बात (bāt, “talking, discussion”).
बदल (badal) +‎ -ना (-nā). The first element in the word is from Arabic.
Regular causative form of बनना (bannā). Compare Marathi बनवणे (banavṇe).
Inherited from Ashokan Prakrit *𑀩𑁄𑀮𑁆𑀮𑁆 (*boll, “to speak, utter”); related to बोलना (bolnā, “to speak”).

Inherited from Sauraseni Prakrit 𑀩𑁄𑀮𑁆𑀮𑀤𑀺 (bolladi), from Ashokan Prakrit *𑀩𑁄𑀮𑁆𑀮𑁆 (*boll, “to speak, utter”). Compare Bengali বলা (bôla), Assamese বোলা (büla), Marathi बोलणे (bolṇe), Punjabi ਬੋਲਣਾ (bolṇā). Also compare बुलाना (bulānā, “to call”).
Perhaps further from Sanskrit *बूर्यते (būryate), a metathesized form of ब्रूयते (brūyate), from the root ब्रू (brū, “speak, say”).

From Ashokan Prakrit *𑀪𑀕𑁆𑀕𑀢𑀺 (*bhaggati), a verbal derivation from Sanskrit भग्न (bhagna, “broken, defeated, lost”), from the root भञ्ज् (bhañj). Cognate with Nepali भाग्नु (bhāgnu), Gujarati ભાગવું (bhāgvũ), as well as Punjabi ਭੱਜਣਾ (bhajjaṇā) from a different derivation.

Inherited from Sauraseni Prakrit 𑀫𑀺𑀮𑀤𑀺 (miladi), from Sanskrit मिलति (milati). Cognate to Punjabi ਮਿਲਣਾ (milṇā), Nepali मिल्नु (milnu), Gujarati મળવું (maḷvũ), Assamese মিলা (mila),
Sylheti ꠝꠤꠟꠣ (mila), Bengali মিশা (miśa), and Marathi मिळणे (miḷṇe).
Cognate with Nepali रोक्नु (roknu).
Inherited from Sanskrit शटति (śaṭati). Cognate with Punjabi ਸੜਨਾ (saṛnā) / سَڑنا‎ (saṛnā), Gujarati સડવું (saḍvũ), Marathi सडणे (saḍṇe), Sindhi سَڙَڻُ‎ / सड़णु, Assamese সৰা (xora).
Learned borrowing from Sanskrit समाचार (samācāra, “proceeding, conduct, news, information”).
Borrowed from Sanskrit सुन्दर (sundara).

From Proto-Finno-Ugric *oŋlɜ (“chin, jaw-bone”).
Of unknown origin.
Borrowed from a Slavic language, from Proto-Slavic *činiti.
Of uncertain origin, perhaps from Proto-Finno-Ugric *ćuća (“point, peak”).

Borrowing from an Oghur language, before the times of the Hungarian conquest of the Carpathian Basin (at the turn of the 9th and 10th centuries), from Proto-Turkic *düĺ (“noon”). Compare Tuvan дүш (düş, “noon”), dialectal Turkish düş (“noon”).
Borrowed from a Slavic language, perhaps from Serbo-Croatian. Compare Serbo-Croatian dug (“debt”), Slovak dlh (“debt”).

Borrowed from a South Slavic or a West Slavic language. Compare Serbo-Croatian, Slovene drag; Czech, Slovak drahý; Polish drogi (“expensive, dear”), from Proto-Slavic *dorgъ. Hungarian most likely borrowed the feminine form of the Slavic adjective.
Probably from Proto-Finno-Ugric *säŋe (“air”). Possible cognates are limited to Baltic-Finnic (e.g. Finnish sää (“weather”)) and Komi-Permyak сынӧд (synöd, “warm air”).

From a Turkic language before the times of the Hungarian conquest of the Carpathian Basin at the turn of the 9th and 10th centuries.
From Proto-Uralic *ećɜ- (“to fall”) + -ik.
[after 1372] Of uncertain origin. Perhaps from Proto-Finno-Ugric *pëčɜ- (“color; to color, paint”) + -t (causative suffix).

From the original stem fi akin to Proto-Uralic *pojka (“son, boy”) + -ú (“archaic diminutive suffix”). Cognates include Mansi пыг (pyg, “son, boy”), Udmurt пи (pi, “son, boy”), Komi-Zyrian пи (pi, “son, boy”) and Finnish poika. See also faj. Unrelated to Romanian fiu.

Of uncertain origin, perhaps a derivation. One explanation is that it is from föl (“the upper part of something”) +‎ -d (nominal suffix, originally diminutive suffix). For similar derivation, compare gyenge (“weak”) > gyengéd (“gentle”).
[after 1372] Of uncertain origin. Perhaps from Proto-Uralic *pürke- (*pᴕrγɜ-) (“to turn, revolve, spin”) + -dít (causative suffix).
From a stem of unknown origin + -jt (causative suffix).
From Proto-Ugric *kajɜ- (“to bend, stoop”) + -t (causative suffix).
From Proto-Uralic *kala. Cognates include Khanty and Mansi хул (hul), Finnish and Estonian kala.

From the coincidence of the Proto-Uralic *kontale- (compare Old Hungarian hadl (“hear”), Mansi хӯнтли (hūntli), Finnish kuunnella) and Proto-Uralic *kule- (compare Mansi хӯлуӈкве (hūluňkve) and Finnish kuulla).
From an unattested stem with the suffix -g.
Of unknown origin.

From Proto-Ugric *säptɜ (“seven”), borrowed from an Indo-European language (Proto-Indo-European *septḿ̥); compare Sanskrit सप्तन् (saptán), Ancient Greek ἑπτά (heptá). Initial h- is by analogy with hat (“six”). Compare Mansi са̄т (sāt, “seven”).
Native development. Probably from a stem of unknown origin + -d (frequentative suffix) + -eg (nominal-forming suffix). For the ending, compare beteg (“ill”), meleg (“warm”).
Of uncertain origin. Perhaps from Proto-Uralic *kaŋe- (“to call”).

Probably borrowed from a Chuvash-type Turkic language before the times of the Hungarian conquest of the Carpathian Basin (at the turn of the 9th and 10th centuries), ultimately from Proto-Turkic *öd (“time”) and cognates with Karakhanid اُذْ‎ (öδ, “time”), Southern Altai ӧй (öy, “time”), Turkish öğle (“noon”).

From Proto-Uralic *künče (“fingernail, toenail”) + -m (nominal suffix).
From a stem of unknown origin + -ik.

Possibly from Proto-Uralic *luwe (“bone”) + the suffix -b, used in an unusual diminutive function. Compare Northern Mansi лу (lu) and Finnish luu.
Alternately, from Proto-Uralic *lümpe (“blade, flat part, width (of hand or foot)”), akin to Selkup [script needed] (laamp).
A variant form of leány.

Of uncertain origin. Either derived from the same supposed stem as lebeg (“to float”); or from Proto-Ugric or perhaps Proto-Finno-Ugric *lᴕ̈pɜ, *lepɜ (“leaf”). The meaning “letter” is attested from the 14th century onwards.

From Proto-Uralic *niŋä (“woman”). Cognates include Mansi нэ̄ (nè̄, “woman”).

From Proto-Finno-Ugric *ńälmä (“tongue”). Cognates include Mansi не̄лум (nēlum, “tongue”) and Northern Sami njálbmi.
From Proto-Finno-Ugric *sula (“to molten, melted; melt, dissolve”) + -ad (“frequentative-instantaneous suffix”). Cognates include Mansi толуӈкве (toluňkve) and Finnish sulaa.

From Proto-Uralic *śilmä, then from szimi, via szüm in one dialect (such as the one used in the Old Hungarian Lamentations of Mary), resulting in dialectal szöm, as well as via szëm and the current, standard szem from another dialect.

From the same stem as the noun szerelem (“romantic love”) +‎ -et (momentane verb-forming suffix). The stem szer comes from the verbal application of Proto-Uralic *śerɜ (“row, order”) nounverb with the meaning ‘to join; to be linked / related to each other’.
From Proto-Uralic *tole- + -ál (frequentative suffix). Cognates include Finnish tulla.
From Proto-Uralic *tuna- (“to get used to, to learn”) + -ít (causative suffix).
From Proto-Finno-Ugric *teke-. Cognates include Finnish tehdä and Estonian tegema.
From the same Proto-Uralic root *tumte- (“to know”) as Finnish tuntea and Estonian tundma.
From Proto-Uralic *suwďa (“finger”). Cognates include Mansi туля (tulâ).
Of unknown origin.
From East Proto-Uralic *uktï (“trace”) or *uxtï (“trace”), Proto-Uralic *utka. Cognate with Tundra Nenets ӈуˮ (ŋù') or ӈут (“trace, way”).
From Proto-Ugric *waŋke- (“to strike, cut”) or perhaps from Proto-Finno-Ugric *waŋɜ (“to strike, cut”).
From Proto-Finno-Ugric *wäntɜ- (“to see, look at, watch”).
Of uncertain origin, possibly from Proto-Finno-Ugric *wiŋi (“end”). Cognate to Finnish viime and Estonian viimane.
From Proto-Finno-Ugric *wekkɜ (“thin”) + -ny.
From earlier *vewə- (compare vevő ‘buying’, vett ‘he bought’), from Proto-Uralic *wexe- (“to take”). Often considered a doublet of visz (“to carry”), but this may not be correct.

From Proto-Finno-Ugric *wetä- (“to lead, to guide, to draw, to pull”) + -t (causative suffix). Cognates include Finnish vetää. The Finno-Ugric root may be related to Proto-Indo-European *wedʰ-, either as loan or through genetic relationship.
From the same onomatopoeic (sound-imitative) root as zúdít (“to pour”) and zúdul (“to come pouring, rushing”) + -g (“frequentative suffix”).

From Old Armenian բան (ban); see it for more. The main meaning of բան (ban) in Old Armenian was "word, speech, saying". The sense "thing", which is the only one surviving in modern Armenian, developed from the notion of speech → the subject of speech → the subject itself. Typologically compare Hebrew דבר‎ (davar, “word, speech; thing”).

From suppletion of Latin vādere (forms beginning with 'v') and either Vulgar Latin *and(i)tāre, from *ambitāre, frequentative of Latin ambīre or aditāre, frequentative of adīre, or alternatively possibly from *amnāre, alteration of earlier *amlāre, a proto-Romance or Vulgar Latin variant of ambulāre, or from Vulgar Latin adnāre (in view of Occitan anar, never *andar). Compare Spanish andar, Sicilian annari, Venetian ndar; cf. also French aller, Catalan anar, Friulian lâ
Replaced s- of staccare by a-.

From a Vulgar Latin *brusiāre, itself of uncertain origin; possibly from a form *p'rustiare < *per-ust(u)lāre, from Latin per + ustulāre (compare perurere), or alternatively from a corruption of *combustulāre, from a change of prefix of ambustulāre, influenced by combustus; see ambūrēre. However, an Italian word brustolare (cf. abbrustolire), from a related root *brustulāre, from ustulāre, also exists. The initial br- may also be of Germanic origin. Compare French brûler (Old French brusler), Dalmatian brusur, Occitan bruslar, buizar, Romansch brischar.

From Vulgar Latin or Late Latin cambiāre, from change in conjugation of cambīre, present active infinitive of cambiō, from Gaulish cambion (“change”), from Proto-Celtic *kambos (“twisted, crooked”), from Proto-Indo-European *kh₂em- (“to bend, curve”).  Cognate to Greek κάμπτω (kámpto), Portuguese cambiar,  Spanish cambiar, Occitan cambiar, Catalan canviar, Norman changier, Sicilian cangiari, French changer, and English change. Doublet of cangiare via Old French cangier.

From Vulgar Latin *īnsemel, which is a combination of Latin īnsimul and semel. See also French ensemble and Neapolitan nzieme.

From Proto-Chukotko-Kamchatkan *ðəlɣə (“finger”). Compare Chukchi рылгылгын (rəlɣəlɣən).

Compound of 裏 (ura, “back side, inside, far side”) +‎ 返す (kaesu, “to flip over, to turn over”). The kaesu changes to gaesu as an instance of rendaku (連濁).

From Old Georgian დაჲ (day), from Proto-Kartvelian *da-. Cognate with Mingrelian და (da), Laz და (da) and Svan დაჲ (day), დაჩუირ (dačuir), უდილ (udil). Svan დაჲ (day) might be borrowed from Georgian rather than inherited from Proto-Kartvelian.
From Old Georgian ენაჲ (enay), from Proto-Kartvelian *nen-. Cognate with Svan ნინ (nin), Mingrelian ნინა (nina) and Laz ნენა (nena).
From Old Georgian კჳრაჲ (ḳwiray), კჳრიაკჱ (ḳwiriaḳē), from Koine Greek Κυριακή (Kuriakḗ, “Sunday”).
From Old Georgian საქმჱ (sakmē), საქმეჲ (sakmey), most probably from იქმს (ikms).

From Hittite [script needed] (šuppi, “clean”). Most likely a Proto-Kartvelian borrowing during the late, Proto-Karto-Zan stage of development (XIX-VIII centuries BC).(Can this(+) etymology be sourced?)On the other hand, according to Ačaṙean, borrowed from Iranian from a word in the family of Persian سفید‎ (safid, “white”).
Related to Old Armenian տաղախ (tałax, “mortar”), Laz ტოლოფი (ṭolopi, “mud”).
From Old Georgian ტანი (ṭani), probably borrowed from Persian تن‎ (tan, “body”). Compare Old Georgian ვახტანგ (vaxṭang).
From Old Georgian ტყავი (ṭq̇avi), from Proto-Georgian-Zan *ṭq̇aw-. Cognate with Mingrelian ტყები (ṭq̇ebi), Laz ტკები (ṭḳebi), ტები (ṭebi).
From Old Georgian [Term?], from Proto-Kartvelian *prcx- (“fingernail; to scratch”).

From Old Georgian ყელი (q̇eli), from Proto-Kartvelian *q̇el-. Cognate with Mingrelian ყალი (q̇ali), ჸალი (ʾali) and Laz ყალი (q̇ali), ალი (ali). The word is also preserved in Svan mə-q̇l-a (mə-q̇l-a).
From Old Georgian ხე (xe); see below for more.
From Old Georgian ჴმაჲ (qmay), from Proto-Georgian-Zan *qam-, *qm-. Cognate with Mingrelian ხუმა (xuma). For the political sense, compare Russian голос (golos).
From Proto-Turkic *ïgač.
From Proto-Turkic *āń(k) (“moon, month”). Cognate with Azerbaijani ay, Turkish, Crimean Tatar ay, Tatar, Bashkir, Kyrgyz ай (ay), Southern Altai ай (ay), Uzbek oy, etc.
Cognate to Azerbaijani alov and Turkish alev.

From Proto-Iranian *hižwáH (compare Persian زوان‎ (zavân)/زبان‎ (zabân), Pashto ژبه‎ (žəba), Avestan 𐬵𐬌𐬰𐬎𐬎𐬁‎ (hizuuā)), from Proto-Indo-Iranian *ȷ́iȷ́ʰwáH (compare Sanskrit जिह्वा (jihvā), Hindi जीभ (jībh)), from Proto-Indo-European *dn̥ǵʰwéh₂s (compare Old Prussian insuwis, Russian язы́к (jazýk), French langue, English tongue).

From Proto-Uralic *käle. Cognates include Udmurt кыл (kyl), Finnish kieli, Estonian keel and Northern Sami giella.

First attested in the Yongbi eocheonga (龍飛御天歌 / 용비어천가), 1447, as Middle Korean 가다 (Yale: kata).

First attested in the Sinjeonjachwi yeomchobang eonhae (新傳煮取焰硝方諺解 / 신전자취염초방언해), 1635, as Early Modern Korean ᄀᆞ라앉다 (Yale: kolaancta). From the now-lost root *kol- ("to flow"), whence also the obsolete words 가람 (garam, “river”) and 걸 (geol, “ditch”), and the verb 앉다 (anda, “to sit”).
First attested in the Seokbo sangjeol (釋譜詳節 / 석보상절), 1447, as Middle Korean 가지 (Yale: kaci). From Old Korean 種叱 (*KAc).

First attested in the Seokbo sangjeol (釋譜詳節 / 석보상절), 1447, as Middle Korean 거리 (Yale: keli).
Perhaps related to Old Chinese 街 (OC *kreː, *kreː, “street”).

First attested in the Neung-eomgyeong eonhae (楞嚴經諺解 / 능엄경언해), 1461, as Middle Korean 골회〮 (Yale: kwòlhwóy).
Compare Japanese 凝る, 梱る (koru, “to bind together with rope or twine”); 梱, 行李 (kori, “a bale; something bound together with rope or twine”); 繰り (kuri, “winding, reeling, rolling up, as onto a spool”).

First attested in the Worin seokbo (月印釋譜 / 월인석보), 1459, as Middle Korean 녹다 (Yale: nwokta). Derived from a root meaning "soft, tender, relaxed, slow". Compare 느긋하다 (neugeuthada), 나른하다 (nareunhada), 느슨하다 (neuseunhada).

First attested in the Jīlín lèishì (鷄林類事 / 계림유사), 1103, as 嫩 (MC nuənH) equivalent to modern hanja reading 눈 (nun).

First attested in the Yongbi eocheonga (龍飛御天歌 / 용비어천가), 1447, as Middle Korean 듣다〮 (Yale: tùttá).
First attested in the Yongbi eocheonga (龍飛御天歌 / 용비어천가), 1447, as Middle Korean 말〯ᄒᆞ다〮 (Yale: mǎl-hòtá), equivalent to modern 말 (mal, “word”) +‎ 하다 (hada, “to do”, light verb).
From 목 (mok, “neck”) + 소리 (sori, “sound”).

Of native Korean origin. From Middle Korean 싯다 (Yale: sis.ta), ᄡᅵᆺ다 (Yale: psis.ta).
First attested in the Hunmong jahoe (訓蒙字會 / 훈몽자회), 1527, as Middle Korean 언덕 (Yale: entek).
First attested in the Yongbi eocheonga (龍飛御天歌 / 용비어천가), 1447, as Middle Korean 엻 (Yale: yelh).
First attested in the Seokbo sangjeol (釋譜詳節 / 석보상절), 1447, as Middle Korean 움즉다 (Yale: wumcukta).

From 청소 (淸掃, cheongso) + —하다 (hada).

From Proto-Uralic *kale-. Cognates include Udmurt кулыны (kulyny).
From Proto-Turkic *kuĺ (“bird”).
From Proto-Permic [Term?], from Proto-Uralic *käle. Cognates include Finnish kieli and Northern Sami giella.
From Proto-Uralic *kule-.
From Proto-Permic [Term?], from Proto-Uralic *lewle. Cognates include Finnish löyly (“steam”) and Northern Sami lievla (“steam”).

From Proto-Permic [Term?], from Proto-Finno-Permic *lowna (“day, midday”). Cognates include Finnish lounas and Udmurt нунал (nunal). The sense for the compass point emerged from the position of the Sun on the given time of day.
From Proto-Permic *mu, from Proto-Uralic *mëxe. Cognates include Finnish maa and Mansi ма̄ (mā).
From Proto-Permic [Term?], from Proto-Uralic *nejde. Cognates include Finnish neiti and Northern Sami nieida.
From Proto-Permic [Term?], borrowed from an Iranian language, ultimately from Proto-Iranian *nagna- (compare Persian نان‎ (nān)). Cognates include Komi-Permyak нянь (njanʹ) and Udmurt нянь (njanʹ).
From Proto-Permic [Term?], from Proto-Uralic *pojka. Cognates include Finnish poika and Hungarian fiú.

From Proto-Uralic *pele-.
From Proto-Uralic *päŋe.
From Proto-Permic *po, from Proto-Uralic *puwe. Cognates include Finnish puu and Hungarian fa.
From Proto-Permic [Term?], cognate to Udmurt пырыны (pyryny).
From Proto-Permic [Term?], cognate to Udmurt сётыны (sjotyny).
From Proto-Finno-Ugric *sula.
From Proto-Permic [Term?], from Proto-Uralic *tuxli. Cognates include Finnish tuuli and Udmurt тӧл (töl).
From Proto-Permic [Term?], from Proto-Uralic [Term?]. Cognates include Eastern Mari тылзе (tylze) and Udmurt толэзь (tolezʹ).
From Proto-Finno-Permic *teje, compare Estonian tee and Finnish tie.
From Proto-Permic *turn, from Proto-Finno-Permic *tarna, borrowed from Indo-European, from Proto-Indo-European *tr̥nós. Cognate with Udmurt турын (turyn), Finnish taarna.
From Proto-Permic [Term?]. Cognates include Komi-Permyak удж (udž) and Udmurt уж (už).
From Proto-Permic [Term?], cognate to Udmurt ческыт (ćeskyt).
From Proto-Permic [Term?], cognate to Udmurt шуыны (šuyny).
Akin to Finnish heinä.
From Proto-Finnic *ääni, from Proto-Finno-Ugric *äne. Cognates include Finnish ääni and Veps än'.
From Proto-Finnic *mendäk, from Proto-Uralic *mene-. Cognates include Finnish mennä and Estonian minema.
From Proto-Finnic *poika, from Proto-Uralic *pojka. Cognates include Finnish poika and Estonian poeg.
From Proto-Finnic *toinen. Cognates include Finnish toinen and Estonian teine.
From Proto-Finnic *töö. Cognates include dialectal Finnish työ and Ingrian töö.
From Proto-Finnic *uni, from Proto-Finno-Permic *une. Cognates with Finnish uni and Estonian uni.
Akin to Finnish varoa and Veps varaita.

From Proto-Indo-European *h₂erkʷo- (“bow, arrow”). Cognate to Old English earh, whence English arrow.
Uncertain origin, proposed connection to Ancient Greek κιβωτός (kibōtós).
From Proto-Italic *frustom, from Proto-Indo-European *bʰrus-tós, from *bʰrews- (“to break up, cut”).
From a dissimilation of earlier *medīdiēs, derived from medius (“middle”) + diēs (“day”).
From Proto-Italic *ōs, from Proto-Indo-European *h₃éh₁os. Cognates include Hittite 𒀀𒄿𒅖 (aiš), Sanskrit आस् (ās), Old Irish á.
From Proto-Indo-European *pak-slo-, from root *peh₂ǵ-. See pangō, pāgus, pacīscor, pāx, pāgina.
From post + ea (“these things”).
From Proto-Indo-European *ph₂weros, from *peh₂w-. Cognate with Oscan 𐌐𐌖𐌂𐌋𐌖𐌌 (puglum), Ancient Greek παῖς (paîs, “child”).

Unknown. Possibly from earlier polcher, which according to Walde-Hoffman and Pokorny reflects Proto-Indo-European *perḱ- (“motley, variegated”), with dissimilation *perḱ-ro-s > *pelḱ-ro-s, which would make it cognate to Sanskrit पृश्नि (pṛ́śni). De Vaan rejects that connection as both irregular and semantically incompatible/tenuous, and assigns no known etymology.
From Proto-Indo-European *wréh₂ds (“root”) and cognate with rādīx.
From re- + *-trō, probably taken from intrō and other similar adverbs.
From saccus (“a sack, bag, purse”) +‎ -ulus (diminutive suffix).

The origin is uncertain. Perhaps from Proto-Indo-European *th₂-dʰlom, from *teh₂- (“to stand”) (a variety of *steh₂- without s-mobile, whence also Latin stō, stāre (“to stand”)) + *-dʰlom (“instrumental suffix”) whence Latin -bula. The original meaning would then be “that which stands”, for which see also Latin stabulum.

From Proto-Italic *terzā, from Proto-Indo-European *ters-eh₂, from *ters- (“dry”). Cognate with torreō, Ancient Greek τέρσομαι (térsomai), Old Irish tír, Sanskrit तृष्यति (tṛ́ṣyati), Old English þurst (English thirst).

From Proto-Italic *ungus, from Proto-Indo-European *h₃negʰ-. Cognates include Ancient Greek ὄνυξ (ónux), Old Irish inga, Sanskrit नख (nakhá, “claw, nail”), Old Armenian եղունգն (ełungn), Old Church Slavonic ногъть (nogŭtĭ), Lithuanian nagas, Persian ناخن‎ (nâxon), Albanian nyell, and Old English næġl (English nail).
Most likely related to vārus (“bandy”).

From Proto-Baltic *ād-, from Proto-Indo-European *h₂edʰ-, a parallel form of *h₂eǵ- (“goat”) (whence Latvian āzis (“billy-goat”), q.v.). The term may originally have been adjectival (cf. Lithuanian ódinis (“skin, of skin”)). A relationship between terms for “goat” and “skin” is not infrequent in Indo-European; cf. Russian коза́ (kozá, “goat”), ко́жа (kóža, “skin”), or Sanskrit अजा (ajā, “she-goat”), अजिनम् (ajínam, “skin”). In Latvian, the term expanded its meaning to cover both human and animal skin (or fur), as well as animal skin as material for making objects, ideas often distinguished in other languages (e.g., German Haut, Fell, and Leder). The original meaning is perhaps preserved in the Finnish borrowing vuota (“(raw) hide, pelt”). Cognates include Lithuanian óda, Sanskrit अत्क (átka, “armor, outfit”) (< *h₂eǵ-ko-), Ancient Greek ἀσκός (askós, “leather wine-skin”), Albanian dhi (“goat”) (< *h₂edʰ-i).

The usual theory considers ala to be borrowed from Middle Low German hol (“depth, hole, cave”), or maybe from the same form in Middle Dutch or German Low German (East Frisian); cf. German Höhle (“cave”).
A different view suggests that ala could also reflex of an old Proto-Indo-European stem *h₁el-, *ol-, *al- (“to flow, to drain”) with various Baltic reflexes: dialectal alots, alogs, standard avots (“(water) source”), alksna, aluksna (“miry, swampy place”) (cf. place names like Alūksne, Alūkstes), Lithuanian alė́ti (“to flow, to drip”). The original meaning of ala would thus have been “(water) source”, from which “place (e.g., cave, rift, pit) from which water springs” and finally simply “cave,” possibly under the influence of the aforementioned Germanic words.
From at- +‎ stāt

Traditionally derived from Proto-Baltic *pek- (metathesized to *kep-), from Proto-Indo-European *pekʷ- (“to roast, to cook”), from earlier *h₃-ép-kʷ-, *h₃p-ékʷ-. Karulis would rather see *pekʷ- as a metathesis of PIE date of a root *kep-, *kʷep- (“to smoke, to cook”), formed analogically from *tep- (“to be hot, to heat up”) on the model of *kel-, *tel- (“to build”). Cognates include Lithuanian kèpti, Old Church Slavonic пещи (pešti), пекѫ (pekǫ, 1 sg. pres.), Russian печь (pečʹ), пеку́ (pekú), Belarusian пекці́ (pjekcí), Ukrainian печи́ (pečý), пекти́ (pektý), Bulgarian пека́ (peká, 1st sg. pres.), Czech péci, Polish piec, Sanskrit पचति (pácati, “to roast, to bake, to cook, to boil”), Ancient Greek πέσσω (péssō, “to bake, to cook, to boil”) (from *pekʷye-), Latin coquō (“to cook, to roast, to dry”), Tocharian A, Tocharian B pāk- (“to cook, to boil”).

Originally the iterative counterpart of an earlier verb *dert (“to tear, to split”), from Proto-Baltic *der-, from Proto-Indo-European *der- (“to split, to tear, to peel”). The meaning evolved as follows: “to tear, to split” > “to cut, to chop (wood)” (cf. the derived form darināt kokus “to pear, to cut (branches) off (a tree)”) > “to make by cutting (e.g., like a carpenter)” > “to make, to do.” Cognates include Lithuanian darýti (“to do, to make”).
From daudz (“much, many, a lot”) +‎ -ums.

From the same stem as dzīvs (q.v.), made into a regular second conjugation verb (ending -ot). It replaced an earlier dzīt (“to live”) (q.v.), of which it may have originally been the iterative form (in case it was not directly derived from dzīvs). Its original meaning, “to be alive, to exist,” was later extended to include also “to reside” (like English to live); cf. the derived term dzīvoklis (“apartment, flat”).
From the same stem as the adjective gatavs (“ready”) (q.v.), made into a regular 2nd-conjugation verb.

From earlier *grenz-, from Proto-Baltic *grenž-, from Proto-Indo-European *grenǵ-, from the zero grade of Proto-Indo-European *ger- (“to turn; to wind; to wreathe”) with an extra ǵ and an infix -n-. A minority opinion considers griezt (“to turn”) to have the same origin as griezt (“to cut”) (see below), with the circular motion meaning coming from certain ways of cutting. Cognates include Lithuanian grę̃žti (“to drill, to turn, to change, to mend”), Old Prussian granstis (“one who drills, who drilled”), greanste ([grēnste], “rope made of woven, wound branches”), Old Norse kringr (“ring”), kringla (“ring, circle”), kranga (“to crawl, to creep, to drag oneself”), German Kringel (“pretzel”), Dutch krinkel (“loop; twist”).

From the same stem as the verb gult (“to lie down”) (q.v.), of which it was originally the iterative (and possibly causative) form. Originally it was an i-stem, as can be seen in dialectal forms like gulim, gulit instad of guļam, guļat. Cognates include Lithuanian gulė́ti, Sudovian guld (< *gult).

The infinitive and present tense forms come from Proto-Baltic *eitei, from Proto-Indo-European *h₁ey- (the old athematic present tense forms *eimu, *iemu, etc. were lost and replaced with new forms derived directly from *h₁ey-). The past tense forms come from Proto-Baltic *gā-, from Proto-Indo-European *gʷeh₂- (“to come”), from which also Lithuanian góti (“to go quickly”), English come).

From Proto-Balto-Slavic *jauˀnás, from Proto-Indo-European *h₂yéwHō. In Latvian, this word broadened its meaning to include also “new,” replacing a previous *naujs (“new”) (compare Lithuanian naũjas (“new”)). Cognates include Lithuanian jáunas (“young”), Old Prussian *jaun- in names of people (Jawne, Javne, etc.), Sudovian iaunis, Old Church Slavonic юнъ (junŭ), Russian ю́ный (júnyj), Ukrainian юний (junyj), Czech jinoch (“young man”), Gothic 𐌾𐌿𐌲𐌲𐍃 (juggs), German jung, English young, Sanskrit युवन (yúvana), Latin iuvenis.

From Proto-Baltic *kāy-a, from Proto-Indo-European *kāi-, a stem of unclear origin. It is possible that the initial *k is an irregular reflex of an earlier *gʷ, in which case Latvian kāja and its cognates might be derived from Proto-Indo-European *gʷā- (“to come, to go”); compare Latvian kāja : gāja (“he went”) with Sanskrit कायः (kā́yaḥ, “body, flesh”) : गयः (gājaḥ, “gait, motion”). Another hypothesis suggests a connection between Latvian kāja and Ancient Greek κίω (kíō, “to go”), κινέω (kinéō, “to move, too put in motion”), Latin cieō (“to move”). Cognate include Lithuanian koja, Sudovian kaj ([kāj(a)]), Sanskrit कायः (kā́yaḥ, “body, flesh”).
From Proto-Balto-Slavic *kas

From Proto-Baltic *kuok-, from Proto-Indo-European *kewk-, from the stem *kew- (“to bend, to be bent”). 
Meaning at first “bent wood, branch, stick,” it soon became “wood, tree.” It competed with mežs (< *medis), the original term for “wood, tree,” which soon acquired the meaning of “forest.” The original “branch, stick” meaning of koks can still be occasionally found (see below). 
Cognates include Lithuanian kúoka (“stick with thick end, pounder, pestle”), kúokas (“stick with thick end; thick end of a stick; tuber; mace, club”), kukà (“stick”), Bulgarian кука (kuka, “spike, peg, wedge, hook, handle”).
Cognate with Lithuanian laikas.

From Proto-Baltic *šlep-, *šlēp- (whence both slēpt and its dialectal variant slept), from Proto-Indo-European *ḱlep-, *ḱlēp-, a variant of *klep- (related to the stem *gleb(ʰ)- (“to cover, to squeeze”), whence Latvian glābt, q.v.).The original meaning was “to cover (with one's hands),” from which “to not let others see (by covering with one's hands)” > “to hide.” Cognates include Lithuanian slė̃pti; from the parallel stem *klep-, also Old Prussian auklipts (“hidden”), Gothic 𐌷𐌻𐌹𐍆𐌰𐌽 (hlifan, “to steal”), Ancient Greek κλέπτω (kléptō, “to steal”) (< *klépyō-), Latin clepō (“to steal, to listen secretly”).
See varš.

From Proto-Baltic *wardas, a masculine parallel form to neuter *wardan, from Proto-Indo-European *werdʰh₁om (“word”), from the stem *werh₁- (“to speak, say, talk”) with an extra element -dʰo. Note the typical Baltic polysemy between “name” and “word”, since the Proto-Indo-European term for “name”, still conserved in Old Prussian emnes, emmens (< Proto-Indo-European *h₁nómn̥), was lost and replaced by *werdʰo-. Cognates include Lithuanian var̃das, Old Prussian wīrds, wirds, Sudovian ward, Russian врать (vratʹ, “to lie”), Belarusian вярзці́ (vjarzcí, “s/he lies”), Ukrainian верзти́ (verztý, “to lie”), Proto-Germanic *wurdą (Gothic 𐍅𐌰𐌿𐍂𐌳 (waurd), German Wort, English word, Icelandic orð), Hittite ḫurt- (“to load, to charge”) (: weriya- “to say”), Sanskrit व्रत (vrata, “vow, command”), Ancient Greek εἴρω (eírō, “to say”) (< *weryō), Latin verbum.

From Proto-Balto-Slavic *źemē, compare zem, ultimately from Proto-Indo-European *dʰéǵʰōm. Compare Lithuanian žẽmė, Polish ziemia, Russian земля́ (zemljá), Persian زمین‎ (zamin) Latin humus, Ancient Greek χθών (khthṓn).
Compare with Avar хӏарщ (ḥarš̄).
From Proto-Northeast Caucasian *hwĕʔnV (“blood”); compare Akhvakh гьини, гьиᴴ (hini, hĩ, “blood”).
From Proto-Turkic *bẹ̄ĺ(k) (“five”). Cognate with Kazakh бес (bes), Krymchak беш, Kyrgyz беш (beş), Turkish beş, Karakhanid بٖيشْ‎ (bḗš, “five”), Old Turkic 𐰋𐰃𐱁‎ (béš, “five”).

From Proto-Balto-Slavic *beˀg-; cognate with Latvian bêgt, Proto-Slavic *běťi (“to flee, run”). From Proto-Indo-European *bʰégʷeti, from Proto-Indo-European *bʰegʷ- (“run, flee”), with long vowel due to Winter's Law. Cognate with Ancient Greek φέβομαι (phébomai, “flee, take flight”). Possibly also Tocharian A pukäl, Tocharian B pikul (“year”).
Compare Polish verb dzierżyć (“to hold”).

From Proto-Indo-European *gʷew(H)- (“to gain”), see also Latvian gaut (“to catch, gain”), gūvejs (“winner”).
Compare Old Prussian geguse (“cuckoo”) attested in Elbing Vocabulary.

From Proto-Balto-Slavic, from Proto-Indo-European *gʷʰen-. Cognate with Latvian dzīt, Old Prussian guntwei, Polish gnać (“to rush”), Ancient Greek θείνω (theínō, “to kill”) and Sanskrit हन्ति (hánti, “to slay”). See also ganýti (“to graze”).
From Proto-Baltic *jḗˀgāˀ, from *yēgʷeh₂ (“power, youthful strength”). Cognates include Latvian jēga (“meaning, sense, point”), Ancient Greek ἥβη (hḗbē, “power, youthful strength”).

From Proto-Indo-European *kelh₁- (“to shout”), which is imitative. Related to Old English hlowan (“to low, make a noise like a cow”), Old High German halan (“to call”), Ancient Greek κλεδον (kledon, “report, fame”), κλήση (klḗsē, “to call”), κέλαδος (kélados, “noise”), Middle Irish cailech (“cock”), Latin calō (“to call out, announce solemnly”), Sanskrit उषःकल (uṣaḥkala, “cock”, literally “dawn-calling”).
Per Derksen 2008, from Proto-Balto-Slavic *kampta.  Also compare Proto-Celtic *kantos (“corner”).
From Proto-Balto-Slavic *kas, from Proto-Indo-European *kʷos.
From Proto-Indo-European *pekʷ-. The current Lithuanian form has experienced metathesis. Cognate with Russian печь (pečʹ).
Compare Latvian ciets.
Cognate with Old Prussian quoi (“I/you want”), Old East Slavic свѣтъ (světŭ, “world; society”), Latin quaero (“I look for”).
From Proto-Balto-Slavic *minˀk-. Cognate with Latvian mīksts, Polish miękki.

Within Balto-Slavic a connection can be drawn with Latvian mustavas (“warping beam”) (compare muštùvas); Slovene mašiti (“fill, clog up”) and perhaps Bulgarian му́ша (múša, “stab, poke”) < *moux-. These forms point to Proto-Indo-European -s- and a root of *mews- (“poke, beat”); compare Sanskrit मुष्णाति (muṣṇāti, “steal, break”).
According to Beekes, the root is *h₂muḱ-; compare Ancient Greek ἀμύσσω (amússō, “scratch, tear”), Latin mūcrō (“sharp point”). However, neither the semantic nor formal arguments make a convincing case for the Lithuanian term to belong here.
From Proto-Balto-Slavic *nogaʔ, from Proto-Indo-European *h₃nogʷʰ-eh₂.
Compare Latvian āda.
Probably related to Proto-Germanic *hulaz (“hole”), from Proto-Indo-European *ḱel- (“to cover”).
From Proto-Indo-European *h₄orh₂-on- (“shore, bank, border”).
From Proto-Balto-Slavic *pírštan. Cognate with Latvian pirksts, Old Prussian pirsten and Proto-Slavic *pь̃rstъ. Compare also Sanskrit पृष्ठ (pṛṣṭhá, “back”).
Probably cognate with Latvian pūst.
Cognate with Latvian slēpt.

Cognate with Latvian sâkt (“start, begin”). Frequently connected with Old Church Slavonic скакати, скачѫ (skakati, skačǫ, “hop, jump”), скочити (skočiti, “jump, leap”), Proto-Germanic *skehaną (“spring up, emerge”). If so, we could be looking at a Proto-Indo-European s-mobile *(s)ḱeh₂k-, *(s)ḱoh₂k-, with the palatovelar present in the Baltic forms (< *śoˀk-) being neutralised after s in Slavic (< *skoˀk-).
Compare Latvian stiprs.

From Proto-Balto-Slavic *suk- (“turn, spin”); compare Latvian sukt, Proto-Slavic *sъkati (Russian скать (skatʹ, “twist, turn”), Czech skati). Also related are Latvian sàucêt, Proto-Slavic *sučiti. Beyond Balto-Slavic, hesitant connections have been made with Tocharian A ṣkārā, Tocharian B aṣkār (“at the back”), Ossetian хуы́рх (x°ýrx, “whey”), Latin sucula (“winch”).

From Proto-Balto-Slavic *tek-, from Proto-Indo-European *tekʷ-. Cognates include Latvian tecēt, Serbo-Croatian тећи/teći (“to flow”), Sanskrit तक्ति (tákti, “to rush”) and Old Irish techid (“to flee”).

From Proto-Indo-European *ǵʰelh₃-. Cognate with Latvian zaļš (“green”) and akin to Proto-Slavic *zelenъ (“green”), *zelьje (“young vegetation”).
From Sanskrit आग्रह (āgraha, “inclination towards, whim”).
Cognates with Tamil காற்று (kāṟṟu), Kannada ಗಾಳಿ (gāḷi), Telugu గాలి (gāli).
Cognate with Kannada ತೀ (tī), Tamil தீ (tī).
From Sanskrit नख (nakha).
From Proto-Dravidian *vīṭu. Cognate with Kannada ಬೀಡು (bīḍu, “house”), Tamil வீடு (vīṭu)

According to Feoktistov, from a Turkic language. Veršinin considers suggestions of borrowing completely baseless, he is convinced that the term is of child language origin (its original meaning being "mother"), according to him, the following are of a similar origin: Eastern Mari ава (ava), Western Mari ӓвӓ (ävä), cf. dialectal Eastern Mari аппа! (appa!, “[an exclamation for a baby to smile]”), Tundra Nenets [script needed] (āppa, “mother [child language]”). Parallel developments in unrelated languages: Selkup ама (“mother”), Basque ama (“id.”), Nivkh ымык (əmək, “id.”), Koryak [script needed] (-aw'-) in [script needed] (ŋaw'gyjnik, “female [animal]”).

Ultimately from Proto-Uralic *ëla. Perhaps by error EES lists Moksha ал (al, “egg”) as a cognate of Estonian ala. Compare, however, Estonian alus (“foundation”), Livonian alā (“down; under”), alli (“foundation; underside”), among others. Veršinin, however, lists “the lower part of something” as an alternative sense for the word ал (al) in both Mordvinic languages. He speculates that the “egg” sense is secondary to the “underside” sense (as eggs are found under birds), a possible taboo replacement, as collecting eggs in the spring was very important in historic times.

From Proto-Mordvinic *viŕ. Cognates include Erzya вирь (virʹ).
From Proto-Uralic *kanta-. Cognates include Erzya кандомс (kandoms), Northern Sami guoddit, Finnish kantaa, Eastern Mari кондаш (kondaš).

Cognate with Erzya ки (ki). This term is to be linked with Eastern Mari кыша (kyša, “footprint”), Finnish keino (“way (of doing something)”). Veršinin thinks that the origin could be the old pronoun *ki (“this”), a correspondence k-/t- then would explain Estonian tee (“road”), Finnish tie (“id.”), Komi туй (tuj, “road; footprints; direction”).
From корхтамс (korxtams, “to speak”) +‎ -ма (-ma).

From Proto-Uralic *kota. Some speculate borrowing from Proto-Indo-European *koth₁o-, whence Persian کد‎ (kad). Phonologically and semantically similar terms can be found in other language families: Tungusic Evenki котон (koton), Dravidian Tamil குடி (kuṭi), Ainu コッ (kot, “building site; place”).
From Proto-Uralic *käle. Cognates include Finnish kieli, Estonian keel and Northern Sami giella.

Veršinin considers this term evidently connected with иля (ilja, “other, different”), the latter being the original form, the root и- (i-) is of the same origin as исень (isenʹ, “of yesterday [adjective]”) and ичкозе (ičkoze, “far”), э- (e-) in Erzya эзк (ezk, “close, next to”), эське (esʹke, “last time”), he compares -э- in Tundra Nenets [script needed] (ŋeli, “other, different”), [script needed] (ŋelimź, “to become different”), Udmurt иськан (isʹkan, “close female friend, close relative”) and Eastern Mari (в)е- ((v)je-) in вес(е) (ves(je), “other”) (where в- (v-) might be a secondary development.) In relation to the last ones, he also compares Proto-Turkic [Term?] (eš, “friend”).
In the Erzya word иля (ilja, “don't [imperative of negation verb]”) Veršinin sees shifting of meaning from "that (one)" → "not (that one)," where the и- (i-) originally has been a demonstrative component, the same as in the Moksha term.
From Proto-Uralic *luke-.

From Proto-Uralic *pälä (“half; side”). The sense of the postposition apparently evolved from "side" to "by the side of."
