A Berber borrowing, originally spread in African Latin and then gradually replacing the native ulva, compare Kabyle tabuda (“Typha angustifolia”) etc., also Arabic بُرْدِيّ‎ (burdiyy), بُوط‎ (būṭ, “cattail”) from which some forms have later been reborrowed into Romance, listed there. There is an interpolation in the Dioscurides locus about θαψία (thapsía) after φέρουλα σιλβέστρις saying that the Africans call it βοιδίν (boidín) (Ἅφροι βοιδίν, left out in Dioscórides interactivo), which mirrors a Berber collective morpheme -īn (as explained by Bertoldi 1947 p. 195 seq.).

From Medieval Latin, from Vulgar Latin *tirō, tirāre, of unknown or uncertain etymology. Possibly from Gothic *𐍄𐌹𐍂𐌰𐌽 (*tiran), from Proto-Germanic *teraną or alternatively Late Latin *martyrāre, possibly with influence from Latin trahō. Cognate with English tier. Compare English tear.
From bashkë (“together, simultaneously”) +‎ -oj verb suffix.

From archaic and dialectal bënj (“to make appear; do, make”), from Proto-Albanian *banja, from Proto-Indo-European *bʰh₂-n-yé-ti, from *bʰeh₂- (“shine”) (compare Greek φαίνομαι (faínomai, “to seem, appear”).
From dialectal bjej, from Proto-Albanian *bera, from Proto-Indo-European *bʰerH- (“to strike”) (compare Old English berian, Latin ferīre).

Aphetic form of dialectal ndëgjoj, from Old Albanian ëndiglonj (Buzuku), from Proto-Albanian *jāgnja, a derivative of gjoj. Compare Old High German jagon (“to hunt”). More at gjoj.
From earlier ëndiglonj, from Proto-Albanian *intellegɔnjœ, borrowed through Vulgar Latin from Latin intellegо̄ (“I understand”). Compare Romanian înțelege.
From *etës (compare dialectal ecëj), from Proto-Albanian *aitatja, from Proto-Indo-European *h₁éyti, present of *h₁ey-. Compare Serbo-Croatian ìći, Lithuanian eĩti. See heci.
Origin disputed. Either from Latin aere (“air”), (already reflected in Albanian ajër) or from Proto-Indo-European *h₁ey- (“to go”), influenced by ajër.
From fill +‎ -oj verb suffix.
Borrowed from Latin fortis.

According to Orel, from Proto-Albanian *sprūgnja, etymologically connected to Lithuanian sprūgstu, sprūgti (“to escape, get out”) and Proto-Slavic *prygati (“to spring, jump”).
Earlier form might have been *fnyj, from *pnyj,(Can this(+) etymology be sourced?) from Proto-Albanian *pnewa, hence from Proto-Indo-European *pnew-. Compare Ancient Greek πνέω (pnéō, “I blow”). A similar development p- > f- happened to ftoh, from Old Albanian ptoh.

From dialectal Tosk pshij, pëshinj, from Proto-Albanian *bʰs-in-je/o-, from Proto-Indo-European *bʰes- (“rub”) (compare Old High German besamo (“broom”), Ancient Greek ψάω (psáō, “I rub”), English berry).

From Old Albanian gluhë (“language, tongue”), from Proto-Albanian *gluxā, from earlier *gulsā, from pre-Albanian *gl̥so-, zero-grade of Proto-Indo-European *gols-o- (compare Proto-Balto-Slavic *galsas (“voice”), Proto-Germanic *kalzōną (“to call”)).
From Serbo-Croatian goditi (“to please”), pogoditi (“I hit”).

From dialectal and archaic helq, from Proto-Albanian *(w)alkja, from *h₂wolkéye-, causative of Proto-Indo-European *h₂welk- (“to pull”) (compare Lithuanian velkù, Bulgarian влека́ (vleká, “to drag”), Greek αυλάκι (avláki, “furrow”)).

From Proto-Albanian *kapa, from Proto-Indo-European *keh₂p-. Cognate to (Baltic) Latvian kàmpju, kàmpt; Proto-Celtic *kawnos (Old Irish cúan, Irish cuan, Scottish Gaelic cuan); Proto-Germanic *habnō, Proto-Germanic *habjaną (“to have, lift”); Proto-Hellenic *kapťō (Ancient Greek κάπτω (káptō)), Proto-Hellenic *kṓpā (Ancient Greek κώπη (kṓpē)); Proto-Italic *kapiō (Latin capiō) and (perhaps) also Old Armenian խափ (xapʿ), Old Armenian խափանեմ (xapʿanem) (perhaps) and Latin capsa. Possibly also an ultimate doublet of kopsht.

From Proto-Albanian *kakja, from Proto-Indo-European *kaw- (compare Ancient Greek κακός (kakós, “bad”), Lithuanian keñti (“to be evil”).
From Proto-Albanian *kakii̯a / *kakii̯ā, compare Ancient Greek κακός (kakós, “bad”).
A derivative of kërcas, originally meaning 'to crack, to snap', thus 'to jump, to dance'. A descriptive term.
Prefixed derivative of thyej (“to breach, break”).
Deverbative of kthej (“to turn”).
From Proto-Albanian *ka-ei, based on a pronominal element *ka and a demonstrative (see ai).
From Proto-Albanian *elaiwanja, based on *elaiwā, borrowed from Ancient Greek ἔλαιον (élaion, “oil”).
From mbanj (Arbëreshë), from *ënbanj (compare Old Gheg ënbaj), from Proto-Albanian *en- (an intensive prefix) + *barnja, causative of *bera (modern bie). More at bie.

According to Meyer and Tagliavini from mbar (“I bring (back)”) (mbar +‎ -oj). Related to Albanian mbarë (“good, right, complete, wholly, etc.”), further related to mbart (“I bear, carry (back)”), Albanian mbaj (“I hold, carry”) and bie (“I bring”).Orel proposed it as a (prefixal) derivative of parë.A formation with the verbal suffix -o-, from Proto-Albanian *-ē- (from *-eh₁-).(Can this(+) etymology be sourced?)

From older mbëledh, from Old Albanian ënbëljedh, from Proto-Albanian *ambiledza, compound of *ambi (“on, over”) (modern mbi) + *ledza, from Proto-Indo-European *leǵ- (“to gather”) (compare English leech (“doctor”), Latin legere, Ancient Greek λέγω (légō)).
Compound of mbi +‎ rojë (“guard”), from ruoj (“to guard, to keep”). Related to mburojë. According to Orel, borrowed from a Romance language (compare Italian imparare).

From mbi (“on, upon”) + ul (“to lower, put down”), from Proto-Albanian *ambi-wēla, from Proto-Indo-European *wel- (“to press together”), probably a secondary formation after mbyll (“close, shut down”). See mbyll and ul.

From *ndërr, from Proto-Albanian *anteros, from Proto-Indo-European *an-2 (“there, on the other side”). Cognate to Old Prussian antars, anters (“other, second”), Lithuanian añtras and Old High German andar (“other”).
Ultimately from Latin pācāre. Source language is uncertain, as is the possibility of a direct borrowing. Possibly from Italian pagare or alternatively a derivative of pagë, also from Italian.
From prapë, from Proto-Albanian *per apa, *pra apa, the second element being identical with pa.

The current form is a participle of an obsolete form *pojë, which is a zero-grade suffixed derivation of *h₃ep- (“to work”). Relationship with Hittite [script needed] (ḫappinaḫḫ, “to become rich”) is unclear, even though there have been cases in which an older -i- has become a -u- (ahu (“beech”) is also attested as ahi in older dictionaries), making it possible for this word to have been *pina with a different meaning.
Alternatively a derivative in -në of an unused verb *puaj, continuing Proto-Albanian *pānja. The latter is related to Ancient Greek πένομαι (pénomai, “to strain, work on”) and its deverbative πόνος (pónos), with uncertain further links.
See active voice form rris (“to rear, grow”).
Variant of ruoj.
From sa.

According to Orel, borrowed through Vulgar Latin from the deponent Latin sequor (“to follow”), in particular oculis sequor ("to follow with eyes").
Ultimately a doublet of shoh via Proto-Indo-European.
However, Çabej deems it a word which has come fairly recently into usage, unlike the ancient borrowing Orel proposes. It is lacking in the Meshari of Buzuku completely, and also in certain dialects in Southern Albania and in Italy and Greece it's nowhere to be heard. This leads to the assumption that it's not a very old term, thus a potential Latin origin disputable. Possibly an enlargment with the verbal suffix -oj.
Syncope of shtekoj (“to set out, take to the road”), Gheg variant of shtegoj, denominative verb from shteg (“path, trail”).
From sh- (mobile suffix) +‎ ngrij.

From Proto-Albanian *staiga, from Proto-Indo-European *stóygʰos (“way”), from *steygʰ-. Cognate to Ancient Greek στοῖχος (stoîkhos, “line, row”), Gothic 𐍃𐍄𐌰𐌹𐌲𐌰 (staiga, “way”), Latvian staĩga (“walking”).
From earlier shtek, from Proto-Albanian *śtaigʉh, from Proto-Indo-European *stóygʰos < *steygʰ- (“to climb”).
Through Vulgar Latin, from Latin hospitium; compare Ancient Greek ὁσπίτιον (hospítion) (modern Greek σπίτι (spíti)).
From archaic and dialectal shtynj, from Proto-Albanian *stūdnja, from Proto-Indo-European *(s)tewd- (“push, thrust”) (compare German stoßen, Latin studeō).

Apocope of *thuan, from Proto-Albanian *(a)tsāna, or *ćāhai, from Proto-Indo-European *h₂eḱ- (“sharp”) (compare Lithuanian ašnìs (“blade edge”), Ancient Greek ἄκανος (ákanos, “pine thistle”), English awn (“bristle of barley”)).
Mediopassive of ul (“I lower”); ul (“I lower”) +‎ -em (“myself”) → meaning “I sit down”.

A formation in -s of Proto-Albanian *awa-deja, from earlier *dej, continuing Proto-Indo-European *dʰōh₂u-. Compare Old Church Slavonic давити (daviti, “suffocate”), Gothic 𐌰𐌷𐌳𐌰𐌿𐌹𐌸𐍃 (ahdauiþs, “tormented”), Old Irish díth (“end, death”), Avestan 𐬛𐬎𐬎𐬀𐬌𐬛𐬍‎ (duuaidī, “we press”).

From Proto-Albanian *wesi, from earlier *ōusi, from Proto-Indo-European *h₂ṓws- and dual ending *-ih₁. Cognate with Lithuanian ausìs (“id”), Ancient Greek οὖς (oûs), Latin auris. According to Witczak, it is the source of Doric Greek βαίεσσα (baíessa).
Compound of an (“on, at”) +‎ tända (“to ignite, light”). Similar compounds can also be found in other Germanic languages; compare German anzünden, Norwegian antenne.
Apocopic form of bliva, from Old Swedish bliva, from Middle Low German blîven (“to remain”), from Old Saxon bilīvan, from Proto-West Germanic *bilīban, from Proto-Germanic *bilībaną.
past participle of höja.
From earlier lemna, from Old Swedish limna, lifna, from Old Norse lifna, inchoative of Proto-Germanic *lībaną (“to remain, to be left”), from Proto-Indo-European *leyp-.
From Old Swedish platz, from Old Norse plaz.
From Late Old Norse reikna, which is borrowed from Middle Low German rekenen. Cognate with Icelandic reikna, English reckon.
Old Norse stikka, from Proto-Germanic *stikkô. Compare Icelandic stika, English stick.

From Ottoman Turkish قونشمق‎.
Surface etymology kon +‎ -uş + -mak. Literally, "to settle mutually".
From Proto-Turkic. Cognate with Azerbaijani qorxmaq, Kazakh қорқу (qorqw), Uzbek qoʻrqmoq, Chuvash хӑра (hăra).
Cognate with Azerbaijani qorumaq (“to protect”), Old Turkic 𐰸𐰆𐰺‎ (korï-, “to protect”), Uzbek qoʻrimoq (“to protect”).
From Old Turkic köti, from Proto-Turkic.
From Old Turkic kod-, from Proto-Turkic.

From Old Turkic koñ, from Proto-Turkic; cognate with Azerbaijani qoyun, Turkmen goýun, Kazakh қой (qoy), Uzbek qo'y. Related to written Mongolian ᠬᠣᠨᠢᠨ (qonin, “sheep”), Mongolian хонь (honʹ, “sheep”), Buryat хонин (xonin, “sheep”) and Kalmyk хөн (xön, “sheep”), but the nature of relationship is unclear; the Mongolic terms may be borrowed from Turkic. Pedersen derived all of these forms from Old Armenian խոյ (xoy), but in Doerfer's opinion this is phonetically impossible. Ačaṙyan too regards the resemblance to Old Armenian խոյ (xoy) as accidental.

From Ottoman Turkish او‎ (o).  Merger of Old Anatolian Turkish ol‎ and an‎ (“she, he, that, it”), from Old Turkic 𐰆𐰞‎ (ol) and [script needed] (an), respectively; both from Proto-Turkic. Cognate with Karakhanid اُلْ‎ (“he, she, it; that”) and Chinese 兀 (wù, “that”).
From Old Turkic [script needed] (öte-), from Proto-Turkic *ȫte-.
From Ottoman Turkish پارلامق‎.
pis (“dirty”) +‎ -lik
From Proto-Turkic *saba- (“to beat, hit, fight”). Cognate with Azerbaijani savaş (“war”).
From Proto-Turkic *ses. Cognate with Crimean Tatar, Gagauz, Turkmen ses, Azerbaijani səs.
From Old Turkic sipir-, süpür-, from Proto-Turkic. Cognate with Azerbaijani süpürmək, Chuvash шӑпӑр (šăpăr, “broom”)
Cognate with Old Turkic [script needed] (sürüg).
From Old Turkic titre-  ("to shake due to fear, anger or cold"), from titiz ("acrid or angry").

From Old Turkic yalıŋuz, from yalŋus, from yalıŋ ("naked") (compare yalın), from yalın- ("to undress oneself"), from Proto-Turkic *yalïŋ (“lonely”), probably a reflexive of *yal- ("to take off") (compare giyin- (“to dress oneself”), reflexive of giy- (“to wear”)).
From Ottoman Turkish یاش‎ (yaş, “wet, moist, fresh”), from Proto-Turkic *yāĺ (“young, fresh”).

From Proto-Permic *turn, from Proto-Finno-Permic *tarna, borrowed from Indo-European, from Proto-Indo-European *tr̥nós. Cognate with Komi-Permyak турун (turun), Finnish taarna.

From Old Church Slavonic звьнѣти (zvĭněti), from Proto-Slavic *zvьněti. Ultimately from Proto-Indo-European *ǵʰwon-, *ǵʰwen-, *ǵʰaw-.

From Proto-Slavic *žiti, from Proto-Indo-European *gʷeih₃w- (“to live”). Cognate to Lithuanian gyventi, Sanskrit जीवति (jīvati), Latin vīvō.
